<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Nine Japanese cabinet members Tuesday visited the
controversial Yasukuni Shrine in Tokyo to pay respects to Japan's
war dead on the 55th anniversary of the country's surrender in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
The nine ministers included Justice Minister Okiharu Yasuoka,
Education Minister Tadamori Oshima, International Trade and
Industry Minister Takeo Hiranuma and Defense Agency chief Kazuo
Torashima.(Japan-Yasukuni Shrine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia on Tuesday reiterated its demand that the U.S.
and British air forces immediately stop bombing Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
Moscow "considers these actions illegal from the point of view
of international law," the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a
statement. "It (the bombing) must be stopped immediately."(Russia-
Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The death toll of the appalling pipeline fire last
Friday near Kalabar, a town of Nigeria' s southeast Cross River
State, has increased to 18.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian newspapers Tuesday quoted officials of the Nigeria
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) on the site as saying on
Monday that not less than 2,000 people including women and
children had thronged the area to scoop fuel on Friday night
before the incident.(Nigeria-Pipe)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Tuesday
that Israel will push ahead its peace-making efforts with the
Palestinians, but will not rush for peace at any price.
</P>
<P>
Touring the southern town of Eshkolot, Barak said even if
Israel cannot find a sincere peace partner in the peace process,
it still can win international support for its efforts, Israel
Radio reported.(Israel-Peace-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Several Japanese civic groups held rallies in Tokyo
Tuesday to pledge for peace and express their opposition to
cabinet ministers' visits to Yasukuni Shrine on the 55th
anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 members of the Heiwa Izuokukai (group of bereaved
families of peace) held a meeting to discuss the current state of
Japan's war-renouncing Constitution.(Japan-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Tuesday
that evacuation of the 116 servicemen aboard the stranded "Kursk"
submarine has started in the Barents Sea as weather improves.
</P>
<P>
The storm in the area of the accident has calmed down, which
makes it possible to carry out the rescue operation, the Interfax
news agency quoted Sergeyev as saying.(Russia-Submarine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian government Tuesday expressed "profound
concern"over the Monday closure of a Serb lead smelter in the
flashpoint Kosovo town of Mitrovica forced by the United Nations
mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The plant, part of the Trepca mining and metals group in
Mitrovica that is divided into the Serb-dominated north and the
Albanian-held south, was occupied by the multinational
peacekeeping force in Kosovo (KFOR) and the police units of the U.
N. mission in the Yugoslav province early Monday.(Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
</TEXT>
