<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilots of Crashed Iranian Helicopter Might Be Alive: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The pilot and copilot of a
helicopter which crashed into the Persian Gulf Tuesday night might
still be alive, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After the crash, the two pilots, both Iranians, went missing,
but "we have evidence to prove" that they are alive, said Norollah
Rezaei Niaraki, managing-director of the Iranian Helicopter
Services Organization.
</P>
<P>
He held out the possibility that the two might have been saved
by vessels travelling in nearby waters, adding that the searching
operation is still under way.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter with six people on board crashed around 23:00
local time (1830 GMT) due to unspecific reasons.
</P>
<P>
Besides the two missing, a third person was injured after the
helicopter crashed near the Saga platform in Iran's South Pars gas
field. Three other people, whose nationalities are not clear, were
rescued unharmed.
</P>
<P>
The injured man, identified as Varghese Paul, a 26-year-old
Indian national, said he last saw the pilot and co-pilot trapped in
the wreckage of the helicopter, which came apart in three pieces.
</P>
<P>
"This helicopter was transferring three workers from the
platform to Kish when a sudden jolt occurred", Paul was quoted as
saying from his hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
He said he was rescued by workers after about one hour in the
water and transferred to Kish Island in the Persian Gulf province
of Hormozgan.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter was chartered by South Pars Company and was
carrying the personnel of a Japanese contractor to Kish free trade
zone, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
