<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaza Port Construction Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Minister of Finance
Mohammed Zuhdi Nashashibi said construction works at Gaza Port
started on Wednesday, a step towards the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The Gaza Port was "a symbol of sovereignty and independence of
the Palestinian statehood," said the minister, voicing his
happiness at the launching of the project which came later than the
date set in the Sharm el Sheikh memo signed between Israel and the
Palestinians in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal, the port construction works should start
within 60 days after the memo's implementation, but they were put
on hold for months due to impediments and hurdles set by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) stands prepared to
cement and develop infrastructure in the Palestinian self-rule
areas, he added. Once an independent Palestinian statehood is
declared, industrial zones will be set up, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The port, to be completed in 18 months, will cost 70 million U.
S. dollars, half of which will be jointly financed by France, the
Netherlands and the European Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
Once a Palestinian state is declared by the target date of
September 13, the port will start operation as a trade harbor
between Palestine and other Arab countries, he added. The port will
make 15,000 jobs available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
