<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Librarians Stress Palestinian Right to Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Arab librarians underlined in a
declaration on Wednesday that Jerusalem is an Arab and Islamic city
that should be the capital of a future independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
The librarians issued the Jerusalem Declaration to mark the
conclusion of the 11th conference of the Arab Federation for
Libraries and Informatics held during the past five days at the
Arab League headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The Arab federation reiterated its rejection of the decision
taken by the International Federation of Library Associations and
Institutions (IFLA) to hold its annual meeting in Jerusalem, the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs support the Palestinian position that East Jerusalem
is part of the Palestinian lands occupied by Israel and should be
returned under U.N. Security Council resolutions. The Arab League
demanded IFLA not hold the meeting in Jerusalem. Despite the
opposition, IFLA went ahead with the six-day meeting on Sunday. The
Arab conference was an alternative event to protest the IFLA
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Arab librarians appealed to international scientists,
academics and legal experts to support the Palestinians' rights to
establish their own state with Jerusalem as the capital, the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
They also called on international and regional organizations to
support the Palestinian demands to restore documents and scripts
usurped by Israel and to help the Palestinians to set up integrated
systems of libraries and research centers.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied Arab East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and
declared later the whole city its "eternal and undivided capital."
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of their future
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
