<HEADLINE> Mideast Should See Peace, Cooperation: Jordanian King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Wednesday called on the parties concerned in the Arab-Israeli
peace process to seize all opportunities to turn the conflict-
ridden Middle East into a region of peace and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal in a meeting with visiting U.S. Senator and
head of the Armed Services Committee of the U.S. Senate Floyd
Spence.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also stressed Jordan will continue to support the peace
process to achieve justice for the Palestinians as well as security
and stability for all other peoples in the region, including the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, the king said the strong ties between
Jordan and the U.S. stem from mutual respect and close cooperation,
particularly in the economic and defensive fields.
</P>
<P>
He commended U.S. support to uplift Jordan's economic and
defensive capabilities, as Washington provided some 300 million U.
S. dollars in various economic and military aid packages to the
kingdom annually in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Washington takes Jordan as a strategic ally in the Arab world
and a major peace broker between Israel and its Arab neighbors
since the two countries signed a peace deal in 1994.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Spence reaffirmed appreciation for King Abdullah
advocating the principals of rights, justice and peace in the
region, Jordan's official news agency Petra said.
</P>
<P>
He said Abdullah's visits to the U.S. in the past few months
produced positive and substantial results in the development of
bilateral ties, and helped Washington understand his vision on
Jordan's future and issues confronting the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
