<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Pledges to Work for End of Cyprus Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia will work toward the end
of the division of Cyprus in accordance with U.N. Security Council
resolutions, Russian Ambassador to Cyprus Vladimir Pavlinov said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pavlinov made the remarks when he received a protest petition
from the elected representatives of the Turkish occupied area of
Morphou, northwest of the island, led by mayor Antigoni
Papadopoulou to mark the 26th anniversary since the town was
captured by Turkey in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The petition urged big powers to exert more pressure on Turkey
to change attitude and work toward a just solution to the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Pavlinov said Russia will press on with its position at the
forthcoming millenium summit next month in New York.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, Pavlinov has also said Russian
diplomats will play an active role in New York and did not rule out
the possibility of a meeting between Russian President Vladimir
Putin and Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey sent troops and took over the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Morphou fell to Turkish troops on August 16, 1974. The Greek
Cypriots of Morphou are now living in the government-controlled
south area as refugees.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of the U.N.-sponsored proximity talks have been
held in an effort to find a Cyprus solution. The fourth round is
scheduled to start on September 12 in New York.
</P>
<P>
Russian envoys for Cyprus have followed the first three rounds
of talks and have meetings with Cypriot officials and other foreign
envoys.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the petition, Pavlinov said Putin is well informed
about Cyprus and referred to the position he adopted at last
month's Group 8 (seven most industrialized nations plus Russia)
summit in Japan to ensure the final statement included a phrase
explicitly expressing support for the just cause of the Cyprus
people.
</P>
<P>
He said the statement, though brief, mentioned twice the need to
end the division of the island according to Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"That will be our positions at the millennium summit in New York
next month where we hope that most presidents will have on the
agenda procedure to talk about the Cyprus issue," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
