<HEADLINE> Egypt Seizes Over 1.5 Tons of Smuggled Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian authorities have
seized
more than 1.5 tons of ivory smuggled from Sudan, one of the largest
ever seizures in Africa, the Middle East News Agency reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian, identified as Mahmoud Hassan Khalil and Sudanese
Ali Hassan Abdul Rahman were arrested on Saturday when they tried
to sneak into Egypt, the Egyptian official news agency quoted
officials of the Ministry of Agriculture as saying.
</P>
<P>
They confessed to illegally entering Egypt for the purpose of
selling ivory, and led security officials to the home of Morsy
Mahmoud Al-Tayeb in the southern Egyptian town of Kom Ombo, where
29 sacks containing 1,525 kilograms of uncut ivory were found.
</P>
<P>
The three arrestees appeared Sunday before a military court,
which will announce a ruling on August 26, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The ivory has been transferred to the Aswan customs office to be
kept as evidence for the case. The price for one kilogram of ivory
ranges between 1,000 and 4,000 Egyptian pounds (290 U.S. dollars to
1,160 dollars), depending on the quality.
</P>
<P>
Before this case, the largest amount of smuggled ivory captured
in Egypt was 130 kilograms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
