<HEADLINE> Draft Report on Human Rights in Iraq Ready for U.N. General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A draft report on the situation
of human rights in Iraq has been ready for presentation to the U.N.
General Assembly in early October, the Cyprus News Agency (CNA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Retired Cyprus Ambassador Andreas Mavrommatis, the U.N. Special
Rapporteur for the situation of human rights in Iraq, made the
report following his visits to Kuwait and Britain and contacts with
U.S. administration officials in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CNA television, Mavrommatis said it was
imperative that he should visit Iraq for an on-the-spot
investigation, adding that during his recent visits he dealt with
the issue of missing persons in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his goal is to secure Iraq's cooperation in
human rights issues so that the situation in the country will
improve.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely necessary for me to visit Iraq for an on-the-
spot investigation and my objective is to embark on a dialogue with
the government of Iraq to see how it will start complying with its
international obligations," Mavrommatis said.
</P>
<P>
He described his cooperation so far with Iraqi officials as "
encouraging", but also said that Baghdad follows a general policy
of non-cooperation with the U.N., which affects his own task.
</P>
<P>
Mavrommatis appealed to Iraq to cooperate and implement the
provisions of U.N. Security Council Resolution 1284 which was
approved last December.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, would be to the benefit of the Iraqi people,
noting that since the implementation of the U.N. oil-for-food
program in 1996, there has been some improvement in the human
rights situation in the country, but some problems continue to
afflict the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary report will be given to Iraq for comment before
it is submitted to the U.N. General Assembly, said the former
diplomat.  Mavrommatis said the purpose of his visit to Kuwait
was to look into the issue of the fate of some 605 missing persons.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwaiti officials had asked for his help "to persuade
the Iraqi government to give full replies to the questions relating
to missing persons."
</P>
<P>
"I also met with the Iraqi Ambassador in Geneva and communicated
to him the information I have, asking for a response within a
specified time limit," Mavrommatis said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the U.N. Assembly, he intends to visit
Jordan, Iran and any other country, if needed, for more contacts.
</P>
</TEXT>
