<HEADLINE> Barak Convenes Cabinet on Budget Ahead of Visit to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Wednesday convened his cabinet to discuss the government's
2001 budget bill ahead of an important visit to neighboring Jordan
for renewing the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of Wednesday's cabinet session, Barak said the
2001 budget, which was proposed by Finance Minister Avraham Shochat
last Thursday, is very important for Israel's future development.
</P>
<P>
The economic recovery in the past year, along with Israel
Defense Forces' withdrawal from Lebanon last May, is the most
important achievement by the current administration, said Barak,
who was sworn in office in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 2001 budget, the prime minister added, put priorities on
education, infrastructure construction, and technical research and
development. Barak promised his government will keep trying to cut
down government deficits and jobless rates.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will convene several times in the next few weeks and
will approve the budget and deficit and inflation target figures,
according to a statement issued by Barak's office.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Barak will fly to the Jordanian capital of
Amman Wednesday evening to meet with Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein, in order to drum up support for renewing the Israeli-
Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two sides have come to a halt after the
Camp David summit between Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
U.S. President Bill Clinton failed to reach a deal last month due
to significant gaps over the fate of Jerusalem and the return of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry officials said Barak will update King
Abdullah on the recent developments in the peace process during the
two-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which has hosted 1.2 million Palestinian refugees in the
past decades, has also a special interest in the Jerusalem issue as
Arab East Jerusalem was once under its control before the Israeli
occupation in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Barak believes his view-exchanging with the Jordanian
monarch is very important at the current stage.
</P>
<P>
To soften Jordan's stands on the refugee issue, Barak, as
Israeli media reports speculated, will agree to call upon the
international community to compensate Jordan for hosting refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
