<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Builds Biggest Commercial Port on Caspian Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran will soon finish the first
phase of Khazar (Amirabad) port, which is located on the Caspian
Sea coast and is set to be the country's biggest northern port, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the port will be commissioned next month when
4 million tons of cargo can be handled, said Abdollah Mohammad
Hashem, a senior official in the Ministry of Roads and Transport.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the port enjoys distinct features
such as links to the trans-Iranian railway and floating docks
accessible by both roads and railways. Once finished completely,
the port will facilitate a simultaneous berthing of 11 vessels.
</P>
<P>
Once the port becomes fully operational, the distance for
transit of goods from the Commonwealth of Independent States,
particularly Russia and Kazakhstan, to the Persian Gulf via the
trans-Iranian railway, will be cut by 455 kilometers, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The Khazar port is being built to relieve the pressure on
present ports on the Caspian Sea and respond to increasing amount
of cargo.
</P>
<P>
Some 41 billion rials (about five million U.S. dollars) have
been earmarked for constructing port facilities while another 47
billion rials (about 5.73 million dollars) will be invested in the
next two years for dredging operations, construction of
administrative buildings and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
The construction operation of this well-equipped commercial port
began in 1996 and its dock is 830 meters in length.
</P>
<P>
Four million tons of cargo can be handled once the first phase
of the project is commissioned, and the figure will double after
the third phase comes on stream in about two years time.
</P>
<P>
A floating dock accessible by road will enable transfer of
trucks carrying freight from Russia and Kazakhstan to this port. It
will play an important role in expanding road transportation and
lowering the expense of freight transfer, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Khazar port will also include a floating dock accessible by
railway, three handling positions for ships carrying fuel, and a
large warehouse.
</P>
<P>
The dock will further facilitate transfer of oil derivatives
from Caspian Sea littoral states to the world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
