<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees Condemn Continuing Turkish Occupation of Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's continuing occupation of
Cyprus, including the island's northwestern Morphou area, is an
affront to civilized humanity, said Morphou refugees Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a petition presented to the representatives of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council here, they also
expressed disappointment and bitterness at the absence of any move
to oust the Turkish occupation troops from Cyprus and allow the
return of the legal owners to their homes.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that any agreed solution should safeguard the return
of all towns and villages, not only Morphou but all occupied
areas," Morphou mayor Antigoni Papadopoulou said upon delivering
the petition.
</P>
<P>
The people of Morphou, she added, expect the solution in Cyprus
should secure human rights and reunite Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the Mediterranean island
after an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The town of Morphou fell to Turkish control two days after
Turkey launched its second offensive against Cyprus on August 14,
1974, which also resulted in the capture of the Karpass peninsula,
Famagusta on the east and the fertile valley of Messaoria, in the
center of the island.
</P>
<P>
"It is a disgrace to civilized humanity to accept that at the
dawn of the 21st century, thousands of Greek Cypriot refugees are
still deprived of the right to return to their homes and
properties," the petition said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots, who were moved by the Turkish troops to the
north, are also denied by the Turkish army their rights to return
to their homes in the southern government-controlled part of the
island.
</P>
<P>
The petition called on Europe and the governments of the U.S.,
Russia, China, France and Britain to exert more pressure on Turkey
to change attitude and work toward a just solution to the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Cyprus is too small to be divided forever. We ask for action
not promise," the petition said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Morphou municipality Wednesday evening will
organize a protest rally in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Build National Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official
announced here on Wednesday that Iran will soon build its own
national satellite with the cooperation of foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign companies have taken part in a tender
bidding for the project and Iran will select a winner to build the
satellite, said Mehdi Tabeshian, deputy minister of post, telegraph
and telephone for national affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said the satellite, named "Zohreh", will be put into an orbit
36,000 kilometers from the earth.
</P>
<P>
The satellite has the capacity of beaming 12 channels, seven of
which are designed for providing audio-video coverage and five
others for telecommunication purposes.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, did not say which countries have attended
the bidding and who will possibly win the project, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Tabeshian said Iran has two more satellite projects. One
called "Mesbah" and with an initial capital of 10 million U.S.
dollars will be operational in the next three years. The satellite
is to be placed in an orbit 800 kilometers from the earth.
</P>
<P>
Another, he pointed out, is a multi-purpose satellite to be
built in cooperation with China, Thailand, South Korea, Pakistan,
Bangladesh, Indonesia and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be used for transmission of audio (voice)
mail, transfer of data and other scientific uses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
