<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Banks Refuse to Transfer Cash Reserve to Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The South African Banking
Council is opposed to draft legislation that will compel
commercial banks to shift a portion of their cash reserves into
the South African Reserve Bank' s (SARB) vaults.
</P>
<P>
If enacted, the South African Reserve Bank Amendment Bill will
allow the central bank to determine itself how much of these
contingency reserves it should hold, the South African Press
Association reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, banks are required to hold a minimum 2.5 percent of
their total assets as a contingency reserve, but are not required
to transfer this amount to the SARB.
</P>
<P>
The bill -- which will be submitted to the cabinet on August
23 -- was presented to Parliament's finance portfolio committee on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SARB advocate Johann de Jaager said the proposal would allow
the central bank to relieve cash shortages experienced by some
commercial banks, without influencing monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The larger cash reserve held by the SARB would save the
central bank from having to inject additional money into the
system should certain banks run into difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"The amendment will provide the government with the
flexibility to control the cash flow in the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new proposals, the SARB could decide that all of the
reserve balance be held in its accounts.
</P>
<P>
Banking Council chief executive Bob Tucker said this week in a
letter to the committee that the adverse consequences of the
legislation had not been adequately addressed.
</P>
<P>
"The banking industry therefore intends to oppose the passage
of the legislation through Parliament," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tucker warned that the additional costs associated with the
amendment could be passed onto the consumer, and could result in
the closing of unprofitable rural and marginal bank branches.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the four major commercial banks held a total of 11.2
billion rand (1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in reserves, 8.1 billion
rand (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) of which was held as cash in the
commercial banks' vaults.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the new bill, the banks could be forced to hold
this cash reserve with the central bank, where it would earn no
interest.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 figures, this would have resulted in an
additional loss of interest of about 1.1 billion rand (159 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tucker said the banks should be adequately compensated for
this loss.
</P>
<P>
De Jaager told the committee that the International Monetary
Fund-- in a report earlier this year -- had recommended that the
entire reserve be held by the SARB.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to conduct public hearings on the
draft bill on August 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
