<HEADLINE> U.N., Russia Sign Memorandum on Aid Action in Northern Caucasus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and
Russia had signed a Memorandum of Understanding on Humanitarian
Action in the Northern Caucasus, the U.N. spokesman's office said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The office said the memorandum aimed to establish a firm basis
for the U.N. to continue to provide humanitarian aid to civilians
in need in the Republic of Chechnya, the Republic of Dagestan, and
the Republic of Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N., the memorandum affirmed that the United
Nations and Russia would continue to cooperate on and coordinate
the provision of humanitarian assistance in the Northern Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also confirmed that Russia would work to ensure
the security of U.N. and associated personnel engaged in
humanitarian action in the Northern Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
It acknowledged that humanitarian action carried out by the
United Nations, its agencies, and their partners was based on
recognized international legal instruments, and the humanitarian
programs of the United Nations, its agencies, and their partners
were guided by the principles of humanity, impartiality and
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1, 1999, U.N. agencies including the High
Commissioner for Refugees, the United Nations Children's Fund, the
United Nations Population Fund, the World Food Program, the World
Health Organization and the United Nations Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs have carries out aid programs
in the Northern Caucasus valued at 30 million U.S. dollars. The
United Nations plans to provide additional assistance to the tune
of 20 million dollars by the end of this year.  
</P>
