<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Up 0.2 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices edged up
a slight 0.2 percent in July as prices for gasoline and natural
gas eased after soaring in June, the Labor Department reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The department's Consumer Price Index jumped up 0.6 percent in
June, thanks to an expected leap in energy prices, which hit their
highest point in 14 months with a 5.6 percent bounce.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, energy prices inched up only 0.1 percent in July,
the new report showed.
</P>
<P>
In July, food prices rose by 0.5 percent, as prices increased
for cereals, bakery products, fruits and vegetables after
declining in June. Prices also were higher for meat, poultry, fish
and eggs.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the consumer
inflation's "core" rate also rose just 0.2 percent, for a fourth
consecutive month, suggesting that most other prices remain under
control.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, the consumer prices
increased at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4 percent,
compared with an increase of 2.7 percent for the whole year of
1999.
</P>
<P>
The acceleration of consumer inflation so far this year was
largely due to energy costs, which increased at a 22.6 percent
annual rate in the first seven months of 2000 after advancing 13.4
percent in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The July performance brought the core rate for the first seven
months of the year to an average 2.6 percent, up from 1.9 percent
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the past 14 months in an effort to slow the economy and keep
inflation in check. Many economists believe the Fed will leave
rates unchanged at next week's meeting, preferring to wait and see
whether the rate increases it has already approved will be
adequate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
