<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research: Refrigerators Reveal Elderly People's Health Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Doctors have recommended that
nurses and care workers check elderly people's refrigerators
carefully to see whether they are vulnerable to illness.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss medical doctors at the University Hospitals of Geneva
make the recommendations out of their research of 132 elderly
patients with an average age of 81, according to a Swiss Radio
International report Wednesday. These patients were receiving
routine house calls after leaving hospital.
</P>
<P>
The study published in the latest edition of the British
medical journal "The Lancet" found that those older people with
empty fridges were more likely to fall ill than those with well-
stocked refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
Each person's fridge was assessed for its contents. The fridges
were classed into several categories: those with rotten food or
products past their best before date and those which were bare or
had less than three different items in them.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen elderly people or 10 percent of those under
observation had empty fridges, according to the study. Women were
more likely than men to neglect their shopping round.
</P>
<P>
Those with empty fridges were found to be three times more at
risk of being admitted to hospital than those who had stocked up.
</P>
<P>
Factors such as gender, body mass index or whether the person
was on their own did not influence the risk factor, the Geneva
Geriatrics team explained.
</P>
<P>
"This finding might suggest that an empty refrigerator is a
sign of a clinically frail stage," the authors of the report
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The doctors believe a lack of strength or of friends and family
stopped people from being able to do their food shopping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland to Send 106 Athletes to 2000 Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Up to 106 Swiss athletes are to
compete in the 2000 Olympic Games to be held in Sydney in
September, the Swiss Olympic Association announced today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 105 athletes have been confirmed by the Swiss
Olympic Association, including 66 men and 39 women, although that
number could rise to 106.
</P>
<P>
The association has left the possibility open of including one
more athlete, the marathon runner, Franziska Rochat-Moser,
provided she finishes a half-marathon on September 3 within a time
of one hour, twelve minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, the list is the shortest since the 1988 Seoul Olympic
Games when 99 were selected to compete. At the Atlanta Olympics in
1996, Switzerland was represented by 119 athletes.
</P>
<P>
Missing from this year's line-up is the reigning Olympic road
cycling champion, Pascal Richard. As expected, the committee
confirmed the Swiss Cycling Federation's decision to omit the 36-
year-old rider from the five-man team heading for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Richard took victory in Atlanta in a three-man sprint, and
attracted plenty of attention when he later incorporated the
Olympic rings into the design of his jersey, after learning there
was no official jersey to designate the Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
Another notable absentee, also expected, is the world number
one tennis player, Martina Hingis. Hitting for Switzerland will be
the country's number two, Patty Schnyder, along with Emanuelle
Gagliardi and Miroslava Vavrinec.
</P>
<P>
Marc Rosset and Roger Federer are the two men's players. Rosset
won the gold at the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
In percentage terms a record number of Swiss women will be
competing, making up 35 percent of the athletes represented.
</P>
</TEXT>
