<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Taking International Aid for Settling Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon on Wednesday denied a
report which quoted President Emile Lahoud as saying that an
international organization agreed to provide 20 billion U.S.
dollars for Lebanon to settle Palestinian refugees living on its
territory.
</P>
<P>
An Nahar newspaper Tuesday quoted Lahoud as saying "
international parties" would offered the money if Beirut abandoned
the long-standing policy of denying settlement of 360,000
registered Palestinian refugees whose homes had been occupied or
destroyed by Israel since 1948. But the newspaper did not name the
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
"This (20 billion dollars) figure nears Lebanon's public debt,
which is an important factor of the pressures that are being
exerted on us," An Nahar quoted Lahoud as saying in an article
entitled "an informal discussion with President Lahoud".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman at the presidential palace said: "It was not an
interview. The president was misquoted. The report has no basis."
</P>
<P>
However, An Nahar, Lebanon's leading newspaper, stuck by its
report. Abdel Hadi Mahfouz, editor of the article, said Lahoud told
him that Lebanon was offered 20 billion dollars on the condition,
but he rejected it. However, the conversation was off-the-record,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Local bankers have expressed hope that Lebanon would accept the
compensation for settling the refugees and pay down the debt, which
is more than 140 percent of the nation's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's 21 billion public debt has mostly accumulated since
1992 to pay for post-civil war reconstruction, a massive
bureaucracy, an army and security apparatus. The fiscal problem has
become more acute with debt service alone exceeding government
revenues in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3.5 million registered Palestinian refugees
scattered in the Middle East. Those in Lebanon are banned from most
jobs and deprived of civil rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
