<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Tricks U.N. into Denying Border Grave Violation: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army has tricked the
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) into denying the Jewish
state has annexed the Lebanese portion of a disputed holy grave on
the U.N.-drawn Blue Line in south Lebanon, Middle East Reporter
Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops Tuesday hurriedly folded their Star of David
flag, removed a barbed wire fence around the tomb and fled before a
UNIFIL verifying patrol arrived at the scene. However, they
returned shortly after the U.N. peacekeepers left, As Safir
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, meanwhile, has demanded the UNIFIL check on two new
Israeli violations of the Blue Line, threatening to lodge a formal
complaint with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and demand U.N.
action to stop the Israelis, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to reports that Hezbollah guerrillas have prevented
UNIFIL troops from getting into the scene at the Sheikh Abbad grave
on Monday, UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel reportedly said "Hezbollah
officials have assured us that they are not blocking UNIFIL's
movements."
</P>
<P>
An Nahar newspaper reported Lebanese reporters and cameramen
near the grave had seen and filmed Israeli troops hurriedly taking
down the Star of David flag, removing the barbed wire fence they
had set up around the tomb on Sunday and speeding off in armored
personnel carriers with all their equipment into Israeli territory.
</P>
<P>
Such a move was made minutes before the arrival of UNIFIL
officers escorted by a mechanized patrol of Finnish and Ghanaian
peacekeeping troops at 1 p.m. local time (1000 GMT) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
One Ukrainian UNIFIL officer, identified as Yuri Sertok, told
reporters after inspecting the grave that "there is no Israeli
violation here."
</P>
<P>
When cameramen offered to give the officer their films to prove
that Israeli troops had fled with their gear just before the
patrol's arrival, Sertok said "since I do not see a violation by
naked eye, I will not be convinced that a violation existed."
</P>
<P>
When the UNIFIL unit left the scene, Israeli troops quickly
returned to the area, raising their flags again and fencing off the
grave with barbed wire anew, An Nahar paper said.
</P>
<P>
The disputed grave is located in the central sector of the
border on the Abbad Hill. The Israelis claim that Rabbi Ashi, a
renowned Jewish theologian who lived 500 years ago, is buried in
that grave. Muslims contend the tomb belongs to an Islamic cleric
called Sheikh Abdullah Abbad, whose name was given to the site for
the last five centuries.
</P>
<P>
When U.N. cartographers drew the Blue Line to verify the Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon on May 24, two thirds of the grave
fell inside Lebanese territory and one third remained in Israel.
Lebanon and Israel had given the U.N. their agreement to the split.
</P>
<P>
However, local residents Monday saw Israeli troops with
bulldozers crossing into the Abbad Hill, removing the Lebanese flag
from the grave and raising their own after fencing off the entire
site with barbed wire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
