<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Continues Contacts with Parties to Advance Mideast Peace March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is intensifying contacts with
the Palestinians, Israel and the United States in an effort to help
break the stalemate of the Middle East peace process, Egyptian
Ambassador to Israel Mohammad Bassiouni said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The intensive contacts are aimed at working out a Palestinian-
Israeli peace deal framework to be discussed at a possible new
summit between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, said Bassiouni, who was in Cairo to report to
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa the latest situation.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after meeting with Moussa that the concerned
parties have been trying to help narrow the gaps between the
Palestinians and Israelis so the two sides are able to prepare a
blueprint framework accord, which can help make any summit
successful.
</P>
<P>
A summit between Arafat and Barak at Camp David in the United
States failed to reach a final peace deal last month due to deep
disputes over the control of Jerusalem, which both sides have
claimed as their capital.
</P>
<P>
The goal of Egypt's continuing contacts with the Palestinians,
the Israelis, the U.S. and other parties is to reach a formula
agreed on by the Palestinians and Israelis regarding what was
achieved at Camp David, Bassiouni said.
</P>
<P>
He added the formula will take the form of a single working
paper, which will include what has been achieved and the ideas to
solve the problem of Jerusalem and narrow the standing gaps.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the possibility of finding a solution to
Jerusalem, the Egyptian diplomat said the solution is "simple,
because there are terms of reference for the negotiations" in
signed agreements and United Nations Security Council resolutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
