<HEADLINE> Investigators Suggest Suspension of Concorde's Flying Certificate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The French Bureau of Accident
Investigation (BEA) suggested on Wednesday a suspension of the
flying certificate for the Concorde supersonic aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The BEA, which is in charge of investigating the crash of the
Air France Concorde on July 25, said in a communique that its
investigators and those of the Air Accidents Investigation Branch
of Britain have recommended to the governments of the two
countries a suspension of the certificate for Concorde.
</P>
<P>
It said that a resumption of the flight will not be possible
until enough security measures are established for preventing the
explosion of tires on the undercarriage of the plane.
</P>
<P>
The BEA also said that the investigation has not ended yet and
it is premature to reach an early conclusion of the accident.
</P>
<P>
The explosion of a tire on the undercarriage is believed to be
the primary cause of the crash of the Concorde on July 25, in
which 113 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
The British Civil Aviation Authority also announced on
Wednesday the suspension of the flying certificate for Concorde
until adequate security measures are taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
