<HEADLINE> Mubarak Holds Talks with Qatari Emir on Ties, Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks on Wednesday with visiting Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin
Khalifa al-Thani on bilateral relations and Arab issues of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed means of seeking further promotion of
cooperation in the fields of economy, trade and investments, the
country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and Qatar stood at 13.6 million
U.S. dollars in 1999, with Egypt exporting five million dollars
worth of goods to Qatar. Qatar has contributed 186.96 million
dollars to 31 joint ventures in Egypt, making it the sixth largest
Arab investor.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Sheikh Hamad also exchanged views on the Middle East
peace process, especially on the Palestinian track, which is facing
difficulties over the issue of Jerusalem, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon arrival here earlier in the day,
Sheikh Hamad said he is keen on examining with Mubarak various ways
to restore Arab solidarity and mobilize efforts toward the triumph
of Arab causes, the recovery of Arab lands occupied by Israel and
the protection of Islamic sanctities in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said he wants to greet the Egyptian people and government,
and wish them greater prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari emir's visit came as part of a regional tour that has
taken him to Syria and Lebanon. After Egypt, he will also travel to
Eritrea, Yemen and Sudan. 
</P>
