<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes Measures to Curb Traffic Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese government Wednesday
held a conference to discuss drastic measures to curb growing
traffic accidents, according to Vietnam News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Permanent Deputy Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dung
chaired the conference, which was also attended by Minister of
Transport and Communications Le Ngoc Hoan and the governors of
northern provinces of the country.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents in the country soared to 11,933 in the first
half of this year, killing 3,920 people and injuring more than 13,
100 others.
</P>
<P>
The number of traffic accidents and deaths were respectively 6.
68 percent and 9.01 percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The conference discussed the 18 programs to control the
situation, including enhancing legal education to raise people's
awareness on traffic rules, exercising stricter control over the
grant of driving licenses, and improving safety of transport means
and traffic infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
A measure to be taken immediately is that as from September 1,
2000 all motor riders on highways must wear safety helmets.
</P>
</TEXT>
