<HEADLINE> India, Iran Set Up Joint Committee to Examine Gas Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- India and Iran have set up a
joint committee to examine all aspects of gas supplies to India,
the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the committee will be held in Tehran from
August 18 to 20, an Indian foreign office spokesman was quoted as
saying to the local press.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the committee was taken during the visit
of Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh to Iran earlier
this year, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Indian side will be led by K V Rajan,
secretary in the External Affairs Ministry. The Iranian delegation
will be led by Deputy Minister for Economic Relations Adili, said
the PTI.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the Iranian proposal to supply gas to India via
Pakistan, the spokesman said the committee was a "bilateral one"
between India and Iran and premised on the fact that Iran was
richly endowed in energy resources and in India there was a
growing requirement for energy as part of the country's economic
growth, the PTI reported.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi has expressed strong reservations over the Iranian
proposal and questioned its viability on security and other
considerations, the PTI noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
