<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Parliament Passes Bill on Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indian parliament
Wednesday passed a bill seeking to ban production and use of
chemical weapons, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported here.
</P>
<P>
The Chemical Weapons Convention Bill 2000 proposes to ban
development, production, acquisition, stockpiling, transfer and
use of chemical weapons and use of riot control agents as a method
of warfare, and also seeks to provide penal provisions for non-
compliance, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, a national authority will also be set up
to serve as a focal point for effective liaison with the
Organization for Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) and state
parties, it added.
</P>
<P>
After a discussion on the bill in the Lok Sabha, or the lower
house of the parliament, Indian Chemical and Fertilizers Minister
Suresh Prabhu told the legislators that the current government of
India was committed to maintaining the policies followed by
previous regimes with regard to the Chemical Weapons Convention
signed by India on January 14, 1993 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Prabhu also denied allegations of some opposition members in
the parliament that the passing of the bill was linked with Indian
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's coming visit to the United
States in September and was an attempt by New Delhi to "appease"
Washington, the PTI added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
