<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Confident of Britain's Control Over Swine Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
Wednesday that it is confident about Britain's efforts to contain
the spread of swine fever which broke out in England early this
month.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the European Commission, the EU's executive
body, said the EU is confident that Britain is having the
situation well under control to prevent the spread of the
classical swine fever (CSF), unseen in some 14 years in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The British government is "doing their best," Andrea Dahmen
told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
She added that London will compensate the farmers for their
losses caused by destruction of the CSF-infected pigs, and the EU
will cover half of the compensation.
</P>
<P>
The CSF is a highly infectious viral disease of swine but poses
no risk to humans. The European Commission announced a temporary
ban on imports of live pigs and porcine semen from England
following the CSF outbreak in Suffolk, Norfolk and Essex in the
East Anglia region.
</P>
<P>
Similar restrictions were adopted in past outbreaks in several
other EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Among measures taken to curb the spread of the swine fever, the
commission said, the British authorities have established a three-
kilometer protection zone and a 10-kilometer surveillance zone
around the infected sources and monitored the live animals and
vehicles moving off the infected sources in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
As a result, only five new cases have so far been confirmed in
the East Anglia region, it added.
</P>
<P>
The EU's Standing Veterinary Committee will meet next Tuesday
to discuss the situation in Britain and decide whether to extend
or lift the EU ban on England's pig exports, which will expire on
August 31.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
