<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Seek More Reunions of Separated Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Prime Minister Lee
Han-dong Wednesday instructed the Unification Ministry to seek
more reunions of separated families caused by the division of the
Korean peninsula at the end of World War II and the 1950-53 Korean
War.
</P>
<P>
"The reunion of displaced family members is an issue on which
people pin their greatest expectations," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed more dispersed families should be reunited and the
procedures for reunions be simplified.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, 100 people from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) enjoyed family reunions with their South
Korean relatives in the Sheraton Walker Hill Hotel in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
United family members exchanged their stories of the past five
decades, posed for family photos together, and used camcorders to
record the entire process of their family reunions.
</P>
<P>
An 89-year-old South Korean mother, due to poor health, was
transported in an ambulance to the hotel for a tearful reunion
with his 66-year-old son, Ahn In-taeka.
</P>
<P>
Lee Chong-pil, a DPRK man who met his 99-year-old mother ailing
with Alzheimer's disease for 50 years, offered a rite for his
deceased father with things for the ritual service prepared by his
South Korean younger brother. Several other separated families
also held rites for deceased parents.
</P>
<P>
Choe Sang-won, a 66-year-old South Korean who was reunited with
his elder brother, said he brought about a family photo, a watch,
a ring and underwear as gifts for relatives from the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Kim Hong-rae, 67, brought with him ginseng tonic, vodka,
tobacco, liquor and photos from the DPRK as gifts for his younger
brothers and sister in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung shed tears when watching
the reunion parties on TV and he felt "a sense of reward for being
president," said presidential spokesman Park Joon-young Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president said he is sorry he could not ease the pains of
the separated families sooner, said Park.
</P>
<P>
"We should use this opportunity to put all our energy together
to leap forward and prosper in the new age," said the spokesman
quoting the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
