<HEADLINE> S.Korean Foreign Reserves Up to 90 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign reserves
rose to 90.42 billion U.S. dollars as of August 15, the Bank of
Korea said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the rise to the fact that domestic
commercial banks returned their foreign currency loans they
borrowed from the central bank during the financial crisis in late
1997.
</P>
<P>
However, returns on the foreign currency-denominated assets
have edged down.
</P>
<P>
In November 1997, South Korea's foreign holdings stood at four
billion dollars when the nation borrowed 58 billion dollars from
the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
