<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okinawa Government Demands Revision of Japan-U.S. Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Okinawa prefectural government
adopted a proposal Wednesday demanding revision of the Japan-U.S.
Status-of-Forces Agreement, which defines the legal status of U.S.
military forces in Japan, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The 11-point proposal, endorsed at a special meeting, includes
enforcing measures to counter environmental pollution within the U.
S. bases in the southernmost Japanese prefecture and revising the
criminal court procedures for U.S. military personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Okinawa prefectural government will submit the proposal to
the Japanese government and U.S. Embassy in Tokyo in late August,
Kyodo quoted prefectural government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The proposal urges U.S. forces to take responsibility in
restoring sites to their original state when environmental
pollution occurs within the bases and also to allow municipal
governments to conduct on-the-spot inspections at such time.
</P>
<P>
The current pact, signed in 1960, does not require U.S. forces
to restore polluted land to its original state when it is returned
to local landowners and bans municipal governments from inspecting
polluted sites within a base.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also demands that U.S. forces hand over personnel
who commit crimes in Japan to Japanese authorities even before
indictment, if requested by those authorities.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government says the current pact, which
stipulates that only those who have committed serious crimes will
be handed over to the Japanese authorities before being indicted,
is not sufficient as some suspects have fled from the base to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Calls for the revision of the pact by Okinawa people increased
after the September 1995 rape of a 12-year-old local schoolgirl by
three U.S. servicemen. The U.S. forces refused at that time to
hand over the servicemen in accordance with the pact to the
Okinawa prefectural police which had obtained arrest warrants.
</P>
<P>
The pact was later revised to allow those who have committed
serious crimes to be handed over to the Japanese authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, the definition of the term "serious crimes" remains
vague. In 1998, the U.S. forces' refusal to hand over a suspect in
a traffic accident which killed a Okinawa female high school
student once again ignited anger among local people.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, where U.S. bases are located, accounts for 0.6 percent
of Japan's total land area, but is home to some 75 percent of land
occupied by U.S. military facilities in Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
