<HEADLINE> U.N. Resumes Relief flights to Southern Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations resumed its
relief aid flights to southern Sudan on Wednesday, after assurances
of safety were made by Sudanese government, diplomatic sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Two planes took off early Wednesday for both government and
rebel-controlled areas in southern Sudan to drop food to the hungry
people there, thus ending an eight-day suspension of such flights.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. relief flights, carried out by Operation Lifeline Sudan
(OLS), were suspended on August 8 upon accusations of government
bombings of civilian targets. Khartoum denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sudanese government accused relief agencies
working in the south of aiding the rebel group Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), fighting for autonomy since 1983.
</P>
<P>
A special envoy of U.N. secretary general will arrive in
Khartoum on Saturday to discuss the matter with Sudanese officials.
The SPLA wants a separation of the largely Christian and animist
south from the predominantly Muslim north.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2 million people have lost their lives in the civil war
and consecutive famines in the war-torn areas. 
</P>
