<HEADLINE> Philippines, Cambodia Sign Accords to Enhance Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Cambodia
signed here Wednesday five agreements aimed at strengthening
diplomatic and economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada and visiting Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen witnessed the signing of the agreements.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Hun Sen was accorded full military honors upon his
arrival at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Later, the two leaders held an expanded bilateral meeting
during which they discussed bilateral and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said one
of the pacts signed is the agreement on the promotion and
protection of investments by both countries.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Mar Roxas II of the Department of Trade and Industry
said the agreement is expected to increase commercial exchange
between Manila and Phnom Penh, which reached only 3 billion U.S.
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
This figure, Roxas said, is relatively small considering that
Cambodia has at least 10 million people while the Philippines has
a population of over 75 million.
</P>
<P>
The other four agreements signed include those on tourism
cooperation, on health workers' development cooperation, on visa
exemption for holders of diplomatic and official passports, and on
the establishment of a joint commission for bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In their 45-minute meeting, Estrada and Hun Sen, according to
Siazon, recalled their experience in dealing with problems
involving rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said Hun Sen talked about how his government was able to
handle its internal problem through the National Reconciliation
Program, while President Estrada briefed his counterpart on how he
was managing the conflict in the South.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders learned from each other," Siazon said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen is here for a three-day state visit. 
</P>
