<HEADLINE> WFP Close Down Women Bakery Project After Taliban Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
closed down its women bakery project in Afghan capital of Kabul
after the ruling Taliban barred women from working in U.N.
affiliated organizations and NGOs, a WFP spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have closed down 25 bakeries being operated by women while
the remaining general bakeries will remain working," Khaled
Mansoor, the WFP spokesman was quoted by the News Network
International, a local news agency, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Taliban last month barred women from working in the U.N.
affiliated organizations and NGOs in Afghanistan. The order led to
the arrest of a U.S. aid worker along with seven local women in
Kabul. The American woman was later expelled from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We were told that we can not continue to support these
bakeries being run by women," Mansoor said. "We have no option but
close them down."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the closure will affect 43,000 women and
children since 7,200 families were getting flour from these 25
bakeries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
