<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin: Sunken Submarine in Critical Situation EDS-Adds details on no sign of life; oxygen availability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Frantic efforts continued
Wednesday to evacuate the 116 crew from Russia's sunken nuclear
submarine at the bottom of the Barents Sea as President Vladimir
Putin describing the situation as "critical."
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose "Kursk" went down over the weekend during a
naval exercise of the Northern Fleet. There is no sign of life
aboard the submarine, Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
However, Klebanov told reporters that "it is too early to
conclude that something terrible has happened," the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Both Putin and Klebanov are in the Black Sea resort of Sochi
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
The crew could be lying low to conserve oxygen and body energy.
They had earlier maintained acoustic contact with the rescuers by
tapping Morse codes.
</P>
<P>
In other Interfax reports, an officer in the Northern Fleet
headquarters said the crew has not sent any audio signals since
Tuesday and the signals had been weak and far apart on the
preceding day.
</P>
<P>
The signals may be hard to discern because of the stormy
conditions in the area, but "bad events" may be a more likely
explanation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin praised the rescue efforts, saying that "whatever can be
done is being done" to save the submariners.
</P>
<P>
"When it became clear that the sub was in trouble, every
necessary step was taken... Not a minute was wasted," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the grim description given by Putin, Yury
Yevdokimov, the governor of the northern Murmansk region, said the
critical moment for the "Kursk" would be August 23-25.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Kuroyedov, the Russian Navy commander, said British
Royal Navy experts and their wherewithal would be used to rescue
the "Kursk" crew. Moscow had earlier refrained from asking for
outside help.
</P>
<P>
Britain has airlifted about 40 tons of submarine and equipment
to Trondheim by a Russian Ruslan An-124-100 cargo plane Wednesday
afternoon, Interfax reported, quoting the press service of the
Volga-Dnepr air company that performed the mission.
</P>
<P>
12 British divers have also arrived in Trondheim.
</P>
<P>
Kuroyedov, the Russian Navy commander, expressed the hope that
"Kursk" crewmembers are still alive and "struggling to stay alive.
"
</P>
<P>
"There should be enough oxygen on board until August 25" and
attempts to save the crew will continue until that time, the
commander said.
</P>
<P>
Weather conditions worsened Wednesday afternoon at the site of
the accident and one of the rescue apparatuses was nearly lost,
Interfax reported, quoting Navy spokesman Igor Kygalo.
</P>
<P>
Kygalo said Russia was "by no means" rejecting foreign help.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is that it is impossible to start using other
countries' rescue means without calculating the effectiveness of
their use, without calculating the compatibility of their
technical parameters with those of our rescue units and battle
ships," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
There is still no final word on the cause of the accident, but
a former Russian Navy commander said the submarine could have
collided with a surface vessel on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Kursk" could have collided with a dry-cargo ship or an
icebreaker, ex-commander of the Black Sea Fleet Admiral Eduard
Baltin said.
</P>
<P>
Baltin had once served as the commander of the Northern
Fleet's 41st division of Project 667 missile carrying submarines
and is well acquainted with this area, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military started the third attempt Wednesday
morning to evacuate the 116 crew from the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
The previous two attempts overnight failed due to poor
visibility and strong underwater currents, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Navy is pondering plans to lift the submarine
to shallow waters in order to improve visibility.
</P>
<P>
A press officer of the Northern Fleet said attempts would be
made in the next few hours to raise the sub from the bottom by
pneumatic pontoons and move it from 100 meters under water to
about 30-50 meters, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Russia has 22 ships on the surface involved in the rescue bid.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk" was commissioned for the Russian Navy in 1995. It
has a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and can dive to depths of
up to 500 meters. The submarine is armed with torpedoes and "
Granite" cruise missiles. The vessel can operate autonomously for
up to 120 days, Interfax reported earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
