<HEADLINE> Singapore Oil Smuggling Firm Penalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Ningbo, a major port in east
China's Zhejiang Province, has penalized a Singaporean oil company
for smuggling, after five years of lawsuits against the firm.
</P>
<P>
The company was found guilty of smuggling oil worth 90 million
yuan (about 10.8 million U.S. dollars) in 1995. It is the largest
oil smuggling case in the coastal province and China.
</P>
<P>
The Ningbo Intermediate People's Court recently confiscated a
vessel and ordered a public auction of a building, both owned by
the company. The vessel "Prim," was confiscated as a fine, while
the Huaning Building, located in downtown of Ningbo, was sold for
more than 70 million yuan at the auction.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, several persons in connection with the case have been
fined or given prison terms.
</P>
<P>
The smuggling case was discovered in September 1995 on an
island in Zhejiang. After that, company staff members abandoned
two buildings still under construction in Ningbo and fled.
</P>
<P>
The court said the company smuggled thousands of tons of oil
and naphtha, in the name of "processing materials supplied by
clients," a means of doing foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
