<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Minister Optimistic Over Asia's Growth Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Singapore Senior
Minister Lee Kuan Yew expressed here Wednesday his optimism over
Asia's long-term growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
"My view of Asia's long-term growth prospects is based on the
way their societies are organized, their histories and cultures,
and their openness to technology," he said at a lecture organized
here by the Institute of Strategic and International Studies of
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Lee said that before East Asia's financial crisis, it was
conventional wisdom that East Asia would become an industrialized
and advanced belt of nations by the middle of the 21st century and
after the crisis, the new wisdom is that the region's
administrative and economic structures are too weak to justify
such optimism.
</P>
<P>
"However, none of the basic factors that made for East Asia's
spectacular growth rates in the last four decades have changed,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the economies of Northeast and Southeast Asia are
complementary and are integrating as trade and investments have
increased, especially in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
After the recent summit between the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea and South Korea heralding the prospect of
stability and high growth opportunities for both countries,
Northeast Asia is "in a much better position, with greater
prospects of investments and growth in the 21st century," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"China in WTO will become a driving force in the growth of the
region. This will benefit Northeast more than Southeast Asia
because their trade and investment levels are three to five times
larger. China's economy has been growing by an average of 9.6
percent per annum since it opened up in 1978," he said.
</P>
<P>
Northeast Asia is also ahead in the new economy, he said,
adding that the Chinese in China are capable of exploiting the
digital revolution and in the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, Malaysia and Singapore are best prepared for the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that if China is not deflected from its present
concentration on education and economic development, it could by
2050 well be the second largest trading nation in the world.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that East Asians now know that given the time
and the opportunity to engage in trade, investments and technology
transfers, they too can industrialize and catch up with the west.
</P>
<P>
However, the Singapore senior minister acknowledged that there
are many pitfalls along the way that can upset this expectation of
stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
Lee arrived here Monday for a four-day working visit to
Malaysia,aimed at enhancing Singapore-Malaysia bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
