<HEADLINE> Woman Filipino Hostage Released in S. Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Abu Sayyaf group still
holding a number of mostly foreign hostages in a mountain lair in
Sulu released a woman Filipino hostage Wednesday afternoon,
Philippine News Agency (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
Lucrecia Dablo, looking pale and haggard, was brought down from
the Talipao hills in Sulu by a go-between of Secretary Robert
Aventajado, Chief government negotiator, and Abu Sayaf leader,
Galib Andang, also known as Commander Robot, the PNA said.
</P>
<P>
Dablo was turned over by the go-between to Aventajado at the
headquarters of the 77th Infantry Battalion, Philippine Army at
Jolo, provincial capital of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino woman, a cook at the Malaysian resort of Sipadan
where she was kidnapped, cried before local reporters expressing
happiness over her release at about 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
From Jolo, Dablo is scheduled to fly to the nearby city of
Zamboanga and then to Manila to be presented to President Joseph
Estrada in the Presidential Palace in Manila.
</P>
<P>
She thanked Secretary Aventajado for her release. Present with
Aventajado to receive her was former Libyan ambassador Rajab
Azzarouq.
</P>
<P>
Dablo was one of 21 mostly foreigners who were taken hostage by
Abu Sayyaf gunmen on April 23 and brought to Sulu.
</P>
<P>
From Manila, she said she will return to her hometown city in
the country for rest.
</P>
<P>
Also expected to be released Thursday are 13 more Sipadan
hostages, including another Filipino, and three French journalists
and 12 local evangelists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
