<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Among Best in Restoring Ancient Books </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese skills in restoring
ancient books are ranked among the best in the world, experts said
today.
</P>
<P>
"If China is not the best in restoring ancient books, it should
be among the best in the world," said Du Weisheng.
</P>
<P>
Du made the remarks at an exhibition of ancient literature from
the Dunhuang grottos at the China National Library in Beijing to
mark the 100th anniversary of the discovery of the Sutras Cave in
the grottos.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 Buddhist scriptures and historical documents are on
display at the library, which has over 16,000 Dunhuang documents,
the largest collection in the world.
</P>
<P>
Some of the scriptures and documents were restored to their
original form by Du, who has helped the United Kingdom, France and
Germany restore ancient books.
</P>
<P>
Through years of experiment, Chinese experts have developed a
unique technique in restoring these treasured documents and books.
</P>
<P>
The paper used is noteworthy. Chinese craftsman choose paper
according to the texture of the originals while their foreign
counterparts use a kind of paper produced in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Produced by hand, the paper we use in China is generally
superior to the paper produced in Japan and has a peculiar texture
the Japanese paper does not," Du said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese also use a kind of paste where their foreign
counterparts generally use glue when mending an ancient book,
which, according to Du, will hardening the paper.
</P>
<P>
The paste's consistency varies according to the thickness and
rigidity of the paper when a Chinese expert restore an ancient
book. "It is a skill learnt from years of experience rather than
from books," Du said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
