<HEADLINE> Australia Downgrades Warning to Australians in Fiji </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia Wednesday downgraded
a warning on safety to Australians in Fiji, saying the security
situation in the Pacific nation has improved since the arrest of
coup leader George Speight.
</P>
<P>
But the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade cautioned that
the situation in Fiji remained uncertain.
</P>
<P>
"Australians in Fiji should maintain a very high level of
personal security awareness and monitor developments that might
affect their safety," the department's travel advice said.
</P>
<P>
It advised Australians to avoid travel to the island of Vanua
Levu and to take advice from local authorities before visiting
rural areas of Viti Levu, where incidents of lawlessness continue.
</P>
<P>
It said the capital, Suva, remains calm following the
appearance in court of Speight and some of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, "There remains the possibility of civil
disorder as a result of further proceedings against George Speight
and his group."
</P>
<P>
"Australians are advised to stay clear of any public gatherings
associated with these proceedings," the advice added.
</P>
<P>
The advice was last updated on August 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
