<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sends 30,000 Workers Abroad This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 30,000 Vietnamese have
been contracted to work abroad this year, local business newspaper
Saigon Times Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 16,000 workers were sent abroad in the first half of this
year, up 40 percent over the same period last year, the paper
quoted an official of the Vietnamese Department of Labor
Management in Foreign Countries as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the target is to send 500,000 workers
abroad a year by 2005 and 1 million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Toward this end, the department has set up a labor export
assistance fund, provided favorable conditions for export labor
suppliers to find clients, stepped up its inspections of these
enterprises and promoted collaboration between them and local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the department is trying to re-negotiate an agreement
with Russia to send workers there in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has also approved a proposal to allow
private export labor suppliers. In the near future, three
enterprises in Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City and Hai Phong will be
allowed to provide the service on a trial basis, but they have to
meet certain conditions first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0137 </DOCNO>
