<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Sub Could Have Collided With Surface Vessel, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A former Navy commander said
Wednesday that the Russian nuclear submarine crippled at the
bottom of the Barents Sea may have collided with a surface vessel
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Multipurpose "Kursk" could have collided with a dry-cargo ship
or an icebreaker, ex-commander of the Black Sea Fleet Admiral
Eduard Baltin said.
</P>
<P>
Baltin had once served as the commander of the Northern Fleet's
41st division of Project 667 missile carrying submarines and is
well acquainted with this area, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Baltin said that the Kursk submarine must have been rising to a
periscopic level at between 11:30 a.m. and 11:45 a.m. Moscow time
(0700 and 0745 GMT) on Saturday.  Judging by the damage caused
to the bow, the submarine had a classical deck differential of not
more than 3 degrees. In such shallow waters, the submarine's hydro-
acoustic system does not work effectively, Baltin said.
</P>
<P>
"The Kursk is an ocean submarine, whose systems function
perfectly at great depths. But at a depth of 100 meters, the
submarine's hydro-acoustic system may have failed to spot an
approaching surface ship," Baltin added.
</P>
<P>
The former commander said that during his service in the
Northern Fleet, he did not allow submarines to submerge in shallow
waters.
</P>
<P>
He said all crew members that were in the first and second
compartments must have died following the collision and that the
surviving crew must be going through a critical period in absolute
darkness.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military started the third attempt Wednesday
morning to evacuate the 116 crew from the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
The previous two attempts overnight failed due to poor
visibility and strong underwater currents, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Navy is pondering plans to lift the submarine to
shallow waters in order to improve visibility.
</P>
<P>
A press officer of the Northern Fleet said attempts would be
made in the next few hours to raise the sub from the bottom by
pneumatic pontoons and move it from 100 meters under water to
about 30-50 meters, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
With the crew thought to have just 48 hours of oxygen left,
Russian navy officials were due to meet their NATO counterparts in
Brussels on Wednesday to consider accepting western help.
</P>
<P>
Russia has 22 ships on the surface involved in the rescue bid
and has so far not accepted offers of help from Britain or the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Kursk went down to the bottom of the Barents Sea while
attending a routine exercise of the Russian Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk" was commissioned for the Russian Navy in 1995. It
has a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and can dive to depths of
up to 500 meters. The submarine is armed with torpedoes and "
Granite" cruise missiles. The vessel can operate autonomously for
up to 120 days, Interfax reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Kuroyedov, the Russian Navy commander, told reporters
Wednesday that hope for saving the crew of "Kursk" would remain
until Friday, August 18.
</P>
<P>
Initial examination revealed that the submarine's deckhouse is
damaged and the shield of the fairing of the two missile silos on
the right-side deck was ripped off, Kuroyedov said.
</P>
<P>
"The submarine lies aground with a raised periscope. The causes
of the accident will become clear following a detailed examination
of the entire submarine body," the commander said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
