<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Minister says Concorde Still Has Seven or Eight Years Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- French Transport Minister Jean-
Claude Gayssot said Wednesday that the Concorde supersonic
aircraft still has "seven or eight years ahead of it."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Liberation, Gayssot said that he
is not pessimist about a resumption of the flight of Concorde but
the plane's security should be first of all guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
"Concorde still has its capacities, but we should readjust it
to the right state," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also disputed the comment by the French press that the
suspension of the flight of Concorde by the British Airways means
the end of the plane.
</P>
<P>
"Basically I do not agree that it is the end of Concorde," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The British Airways suspended the flight of Concorde on Tuesday
and its flying certificate on Wednesday, three weeks after the
crash of the Air France Concorde which killed 113 people.
</P>
<P>
Air France has suspended the flight of Concorde since the crash
on July 25.
</P>
<P>
The French Bureau of Accident Investigation will submit a
report to the minister on August 25 or 26 to propose extra
security measures for the plane.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French and British officials and experts will meet
on Thursday in London to decide the withdrawal of the flying
certificate for Concorde. 
</P>
</TEXT>
