<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 109 hectares of forested area was burnt down to
ashes on Tuesday in 19 forest fires in different parts of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Forestry Ministry said on Tuesday that 21,242 hectares
of forested area had been burnt down to ashes in 1,303 fires since
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- A hospital with 120-bed capacity constructed by the Singapore
Red Crescent Tuesday opened to service in Turkey's western city
Izmit which was hit by a devastating earthquake on August 17
last year.
</P>
<P>
Ertan Gonen, chairman of Turkish Red Crescent said that the
Turkish people were working very hard to heal the wounds of the
quake.
</P>
<P>
"We had great sufferings in August 17 quake. But we left all
these in the past. Many regions need hospitals and schools. Red
Crescent cooperates with the other Red Cross Federations in the
world to meet these needs," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Security Forces seized a great deal of dynamite and
other explosives in Kizilcukur village in Tavsanli township of
western Kutahya province on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Acting on a tip-off, the security forces raided two houses in
the village and seized large quantities of various type dynamites
and other explosives.
</P>
<P>
Two suspects were taken into custody in the operation. A full
investigation into the explosives was underway.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Libya has asked Turkey to assist in determining the location
of mine fields, left over from World War II, and eliminating them.
</P>
<P>
The request was put by Deputy Speaker of Libyan Parliament Ahmet

Ibrahim on Tuesday to a Turkish delegation which is visiting Libya.
</P>
