<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and left-wing Meretz leader
Yossi Sarid failed to reach an agreement on terms for Meretz's
return to the government. They agreed to meet again in a couple of
days.
</P>
<P>
During this period, Barak reportedly plans to gauge the chances
of getting the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party back into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Meretz ministers resigned their cabinet posts in June in an
effort to help Barak keep Shas in the coalition, but Shas ministers
eventually quit as well, citing differences with the prime
minister's peace policies.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli government wants to cut the water quota for
agricultural use by 50 percent in 2001, following an already steep
cut of 40 percent this year, according to an agreement reached by
related authorities.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Agriculture Ministry estimated that the
loss of income and direct losses from dried-up orchards, hothouses
and fields would total 2 billion Shekels (about 500 million U.S.
dollars). Some 10,000 agricultural workers will lose their jobs
under a 50 percent cut.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 3 billion shekels (about 750
million dollars) to develop new water resources. However, even if
the investment proves fruitful, it will take five years before
results are seen.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Tel Aviv police in Israel are investigating whether the
deaths of four women on Tuesday in a brothel fire was part of a
recent series of fires in sex shops and brothels.
</P>
<P>
The torching of a south Tel Aviv apartment that functioned as a
brothel killed the four women who lived and worked there early
Tuesday morning. The victims have not yet been identified.
</P>
<P>
Acting Interior Minister Haim Ramon has appointed a three-member
committee to investigate the cause of the fire, the firefighters'
response to it, and coordination between firefighters and other
emergency services at the scene.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli acting Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami believes that
a second trilateral summit meeting between Israel, the Palestinian
National Authority and the United States will be possible next
month, but should only be held after careful preparation that will
ensure its success.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami Tuesday night briefed Barak and senior negotiator
attorney Gilad Sher on the results of his trip to a series of
countries to explain the Israeli position on the peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
