<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Asks People to Rebuild Democratic Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid Wednesday urged the Indonesian people to rebuild their
democratic values and nationalist spirit inherited from the
republic's founding fathers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a plenary session of the House of Representatives
ahead of the 55th anniversary of the country's independence day
which falls on August 17, Wahid noted that democracy and
nationalism are a process and they are not born and formed
naturally.
</P>
<P>
the founding fathers of this republic agreed to lay the
foundation for the Indonesian nationalistic bonds based on common
destiny and ideals, he said, noting that they strongly opposed
attempts to colonize Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Wahid warned against justifying violence in the name of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Should we in the name of democracy -- consciously or
unconsciously -- agree to give a nod to let violent acts occur in
the society, to use hatred and vengeance as an instrument to
sideline political opponents, or, to exploit the previous
government's mistakes and loopholes as a pretext to justify
separatist movements, it could be assured that the true meaning of
democracy as a rational process to deal with the prevailing
conflicts would be difficult to materialize," stressed the
president.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the efforts to redefine, reorient and
reproduce national and democratic values are indeed urgently
needed.
</P>
<P>
He also said he interpreted the proclamation of independence
itself as the pinnacle of the Indonesian people's agreement to
embody its common life through the formation of a nation-state,
which is free, sovereign and democratic.
</P>
<P>
"This republic belongs to all Indonesian people," he declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
