<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Urges Policy Continuity After General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai on Wednesday urged that the current government's economic
and social reform measures should be continued after the upcoming
general election, which is expected to be held in October this
year.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the country's annual economic forum
here,which is participated by key politicians, business circles
and foreign diplomats, he said that to deal with the problems the
country now faces, policy continuity is of great importance.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the current problems, namely bad loans
in the financial sector, hike of oil prices, weakening of the
currency, slide in agriculture products, unemployment and the
people's welfare are not as severe as those seen in the financial
disaster three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"They are normal problems for every country, and we are
confident of managing them if the related policy measures are kept
on going," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Positive signs have already been seen in tackling with the
mentioned issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Within this year, the non-performing loans (NPL) in Thailand's
finance sector have decreased from 40 percent of the total bank
lending to 32 percent, and are hoped to decline to single digit at
the end of the year, according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate is also dropping while a social safety
network is taking the shape, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
The weakening baht may cause the problem of inflation, he said,
but it also boosts the country's export and help speed up the
overall economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Those signs are believed to help bring back foreign investments,
which are thought to be vital for the country's recovery and
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of the reoccurrence of the
economic crisis, but said the economy is not yet back to the sound
situation prior to the crisis although it is recovering.
</P>
<P>
The current government is expected to dissolve the parliament
in one and a half months' time. A general election will then be
held to select the next government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
