<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai FM Sees No Possibility of New Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Finance Minister
Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said here Wednesday that there is almost no
likelihood of a new economic crisis because the macroeconomic
situation in the country now does not meet the definition of a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
There is no total loss of foreign reserves, no loss of
confidence in the financial institutions and no panic capital
outflows now in Thailand, all of which can be used to define a
crisis, he said at an annual economic review forum organized by
The Bangkok Post and a few other institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, he agreed that the economy is not recovering as fast
as expected due to some unfavorable factors, such as the
adjustment of the U.S. economy and the rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
He compared Thai economic recovery to an airplane with four
engines -- public spending, exports, private investment and
consumption, which he said are beginning to work one after the
other.
</P>
<P>
But to sustain the recovery, he said, Thailand needs to further
work on the huge non-performing loans, which amount to 40 billion
U.S. dollars, and bank recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
He said recovery can happen with impaired financial
institutions, but full recovery can't happen without fully
repaired financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Thailand should also try its best to absorb foreign investment
and work out measures that help restore confidence in the
financial institutions, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
While Thailand needs to create a favorable domestic environment
by itself, some external factors, such as the adjustment of the U.
S. economy and the economic recovery of Japan, will also play a
role in the pace of Thailand's recovery, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
