<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Maintains Cooperation on Food Security Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) will continue to be obliged by an agreement
on food security reserve, aimed at ensuring adequate food supply
in the region, according to a statement of the Thai Ministry of
Commerce available here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by the five founders of the ASEAN --
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand --
in Bali in 1976, said the establishment of the ASEAN Food Security
Reserve was needed and meant to require the five ASEAN founders to
maintain within their national borders agreed quantities of basic
food stocks, particularly rice, as a matter of national policy,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was part of the Declaration of ASEAN
Concord, also included the establishment of the ASEAN Emergency
Rice, aimed at reserving the major foodstuff for meeting emergency
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Each of the five ASEAN members is required to earmark rice
within or above its national reserve, totally accounting for at
least 50,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The five ASEAN founders also agreed that a country facing any
food problem would directly notify the others of the emergency,
and the other countries would take immediate actions to make
necessary arrangements to ensure immediate and speedy release of
the require rice.
</P>
<P>
Prices, terms, and conditions of payments in respect of the
rice released under the emergency arrangement would be subject to
direct negotiations, and the requesting ASEAN member would have to
inform the ASEAN Food Security Reserve Board of its request to the
other ASEAN member partners.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, ASEAN members which have to release
earmarked rice to meet either their own emergency requirements, or
emergency requirements of other members would have to take steps
to re-fill the rice so that the earmarked quantity of the
countries would be restored to the agreed levels.
</P>
<P>
Governments of the ASEAN member countries also agreed to
coordinate in their national food stock policies, which take
policies of other members into account, aiming to maintain a
minimum safe level for the ASEAN Food Security Reserve, the
statement noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
