<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Optimistic Over Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
optimistic that the Abu Sayyaf will finally release anytime soon
the remaining hostages it has been holding in Jolo since April,
negotiators said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado said he was to go
to Jolo to discuss with Abu Sayyaf leader Ghalib Andang alias
Commander Robot the final details for the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
"We'll make some finishing touches. Former Libyan Ambassador
Rajab Abdulaziz Azzarouq and I will clear up some things with
Robot," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado said he remains optimistic that the Abu Sayyaf would
release all of the hostages. He said President Joseph Estrada told
him to ensure the hostages' safe release.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Aventajado said a jet from Libya, which
arrived in Manila Monday night, would be stationed only at the
Ninoy Aquino International Airport (NAIA) here.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the Libyan plane has raised hopes for the speedy
release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
"The plane will be there at the NAIA in the meantime," he said,
when asked whether the plane would be flown to Jolo.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Abu Sayyaf has released six Malaysians, two Germans
and three local Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group is still holding hostage 14 of the 21 people
abducted in April from Malaysia's Sipadan island and then moved to
the southern Philippine island province of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
The 14 Sipadan hostages consist of three Malaysians, two
Germans,two French, two Finns, two South Africans, two Filipinos
and a Lebanese. The rebels are also holding three French
journalists and 13 local Filipinos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
