<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government Urged to Remove Gas Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The petroleum industry in Kenya
has urged the government to remove all taxes on liquid petroleum
gas and gas-cooking appliances for the sake of environment
protection.
</P>
<P>
In a proposal to the Ministry of Finance, the industry said
this will make the products affordable to more Kenyans and shift
demand from wood fuel to gas, a cleaner and more efficient energy,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The industry argued that demand for charcoal and related wood
fuel is a major contributor to environmental degradation and
deforestation in the country, saying that wood fuel meets more
than 70 percent of Kenya's energy needs which put intense pressure
on the country's forests.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, the industry called for a deliberate policy to
shift demand from wood fuel to liquefied petroleum gas, therefore
asking for the elimination of taxes on gas and gas-cooking
appliances including cylinders, regulators, cookers and grills.
</P>
<P>
The industry added that such a move will reduce the prices of
gas-cooking appliances, helping Kenyans afford to such products.
</P>
<P>
At present, per capita gas consumption in Kenya is only 1.9
kilograms compared to Senegal, whose per capita consumption is 5.5
kilograms, the industry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
