<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acute Food Shortage in Kenya: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is among 16 African
countries facing severe food shortages, according to the 2000
annual report by the U.N. World Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO).
</P>
<P>
 The FAO also painted a gloomy picture for the coming October
harvest, saying that the long rains cropping season (March-May),
which normally accounts for 80 percent of total annual food
production, "has already failed due to a severe drought".
</P>
<P>
Uganda, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Sudan and Somalia are also among
the countries hit by the prolonged drought, said the report, which
is to be launched on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 3.3 million Kenyans need urgent food assistance,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Except for Western and Nyanza Provinces, the other five
provinces in Kenya have received no rain or little in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
The severe drought, the worst in 42 years for the east African
country, has caused widespread crop failure and livestock losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
