<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's GDP Growth Dips by 1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's economic growth slowed
further in May, hurt by a prolonged drought that has undermined
farm and industrial production, the Central Bank of Kenya has said.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly economic review released here Tuesday, the bank
said Gross Domestic Product (GDP) grew a real 1.0 percent in the
12 months to May this year, compared to 1.1 percent in the
previous month and 1.4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is currently experiencing its worst drought in four
decades and a power rationing program has cut supplies to industry
to just 32 hours a week and also hit agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
"The slowdown in economic performance is expected to continue
as a result of the on-going drought, electricity and water
rationing and other structural factors which have impacted
adversely on the economy," the bank said in the economic review.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank said the on-going structural reforms and the
resumption of financial support by international development
partners are expected to impact positively on the growth of the
economy and the government hopes to increase GDP growth to 5.5
percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund last month agreed to advance a
198-million-U.S. dollar three-year loan to Kenya, while the World
Bank also approved a 150-million-dollar credit to the country
early this month.
</P>
<P>
Improvement in the country's economy is expected to be slow
because of the power crisis and droughts, the bank added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
