<HEADLINE> Internet Usage in New Zealand Reaches 63 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Internet usage in New
Zealand has reached 63 percent, compared with 50 percent in
Australia, Red Sheriff, the largest specialist Internet audience
measurement and research company in the Asia-Pacific region, said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the company forecast that around 65 percent
of New Zealanders will use the Internet over the forthcoming 12
months.
</P>
<P>
"The force of the Net however shows no signs of abating amongst
the emerging e-generation, with a staggering 81 percent of young
New Zealanders (16-29 years old) having surfed the Net," it said.
</P>
<P>
Based on its latest survey, the company said the Net will
continue to be a significant force in shaping New Zealanders'
lifestyles with 75 percent now using it on a weekly basis,
primarily for e-mail communications (34 percent); one in four for
work; and a further 21 percent for leisure- or entertainment-
related activities.
</P>
<P>
Internet-users are spending less time viewing TV, listening to
the radio or reading newspapers or magazines, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
