<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Starts Third Attempt to Rescue Crew of Crippled Sub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian military started a
third attempt Wednesday to evacuate the 116 crew from the Kursk
nuclear submarine that is stranded at the bottom of the Barents
Sea since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The previous two attempts overnight failed due to poor
visibility and strong underwater currents, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The first submersible capsule was unable to dock with the sub
in the night operation and had to be brought to surface to restore
its life-support system.
</P>
<P>
"It has exhausted its resources," Tass quoted an officer with
the Northern Fleet headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The visibility for the capsule decreased to zero when it was
enveloped by sand and silt suspensions, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
With the crew thought to have just 48 hours of oxygen left,
Russian navy officials were due to meet their NATO counterparts in
Brussels on Wednesday to consider accepting western help.
</P>
<P>
Russia has 22 ships on the surface involved in the rescue bid
and has so far not accepted offers of help from Britain or the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose "Kursk" went down to the bottom of the Barents
Sea on Sunday while attending a routing exercise of the Russian
Northern Fleet. It is not clear whether there are any casualties
among the servicemen aboard the vessel.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the accident is still unknown and all versions are
being checked, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Tuesday. He
listed collision with a different object or an explosion in the
first compartment of the submarine as among the most probable
scenarios.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were two U.S. submarines nearby at
the time of the accident and they reported the sound of an
explosion.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk" was commissioned for the Russian Navy in 1995. It
has a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and can dive to depths of
up to 500 meters. The submarine is armed with torpedoes and "
Granite" cruise missiles. The vessel can operate autonomously for
up to 120 days, the Interfax news agency reported earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
