<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warm Water, Slow Wind Blamed for Triggering Bohai Red Tides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Higher water temperatures, the
sun and the wind are blamed for triggering frequent outbreaks of
large-scale red tides last month in the polluted Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
Li Xingming, an expert with the China Maritime Supervision
Corps under the State Oceanic Administration of China, said
excessive nitrogen and phosphorus pumped into the sea are the main
reasons for four red tides last month.
</P>
<P>
But without high water temperatures, enough sunshine and wind,
or the right weather conditions, there would be no red tides, said
Li.
</P>
<P>
About 20 to 30 red tides are expected to occur this year in the
coastal sea waters, said the experts.
</P>
<P>
Red tides are mainly caused by pollution from land and large-
scale farming in coastal waters, which produce too much nitrogen
and phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
China has experienced increasing red tides off the coast since
the 1990s due to increasing pollution caused by industrial waste
water, according to a recent report issued by the State Oceanic
Administration.
</P>
<P>
A total of 45 large-scale red tides occurred between 1997 and
1999, causing direct economic losses of 240 million U.S. dollars,
Guangming Daily reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strict Rule for Justice Officials Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders will have to be
responsible for their subordinates who break the law or violate
disciplinary regulations in south China's Guangdong Provincial
Justice Department, according to a strict internal rule
established recently.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen officials in the department have signed agreements in
this regard. According to the agreements, in a given year an
official will have no chance of promotion if any one of the
subordinates is found guilty of violating disciplinary regulations
or the criminal law; should there be two cases of violations, the
official will have to take the blame and ask to resign, today's "
Legal Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The rule was established as the provincial department has been
stepping up its efforts to combat corruption. In recent years a
number of abuses have been uncovered in the department, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Eight Chinese cities, namely
Beijing, Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Hohhot, Zhengzhou,
Guiyang and Lanzhou, reported slight air pollution today, with the
highest pollution reading at 148 in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two or fairly good air
quality was recorded in the following 27 cities: Shenyang, Dalian
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Wuhan,
Changsha, Guangzhou, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Chongqing, Chengdu, Xi'an,
Xining, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of the cities, except Chongqing and Guiyang,
where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Seven cities -- Xiamen, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Nanning, Haikou,
Kunming and Lhasa -- reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution readings: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President: Economic Recovery Aimed at Improving Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid said here Wednesday that the national economic recovery
program is aimed at increasing the quality of the people's life.
</P>
<P>
The rebuilding of the national economy is also aimed at
achieving the ideal of independence, said the president in his
state address before the House of Representatives (DPR) to
commemorate the 55th anniversary of the national independence day
which is due on August 17
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, the crisis that is entering its third year
has obliged us to undertake various recovery policies which often
cause weighty impacts on the social and economic lives and which
are politically sensitive," Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the same occasion, DPR Speaker Akbar Tandjung
said the DPR leadership attentively observes the government's
efforts in overcoming the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that all the ongoing crisis recovery programs, which
are now being implemented, could be continued or even increased,
especially if they are connected to the presence of a decision on
entrusting the duties to the vice president to lead -- on a daily
basis -- the governmental technical activities, and the
possibility of restructuring and reshuffling the cabinet,"
Tandjung said.
</P>
<P>
Wahid also added that the quantity and quality of the various
instruments to carry out the goal of economic justice will be
continuously improved.
</P>
<P>
In connection with the global situation, Wahid said the
rebuilding of the country's economy which is aimed at achieving
the ideal of independence will be carried out within the ever-
changing global environment.
</P>
<P>
He added that economic globalization requires the
implementation of and the respect for human rights and the
protection and preservation of the environment.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, the economic management has also to be based
on the just, firm and positive rules aiming to safeguard the
interests of the workers, the consumers and the environment. These
interests are weighted to and in line with the interests of the
government. At the same time, they have to be measured in a
balanced manner with the interests of the investors and business
society at large," the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
