<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Pledges to Lessen Dominant Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid promised here Wednesday that his government will lessen its
dominant role, saying that there are still many Indonesian people
engulfed in a miserable condition.
</P>
<P>
Wahid made the statement before the House of Representatives (
DPR) plenary session, during which he delivered a state address to
commemorate the 55th of the national independence day which falls
on August 17.
</P>
<P>
"It is indeed ironical that during this auspicious event, there
are many citizens of our nation still engulfed in a miserable
condition because they are not as yet free from fear over the fate
and safety of their family members as well as of their own," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
"The urban poor people are not yet completely free from being
sidelined and chased away from their own dwelling places," Wahid
said, adding that "freedom from a protracted suffering has not yet
been enjoyed by some of our fellow citizens who are still engulfed
by the structural poverty."
</P>
<P>
"The government is, therefore, highly committed to lessening
its dominant role," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that all governmental apparatuses need to improve
their capability to assume their facilitating role. "We should all
be aware that it is indeed of paramount importance to build a
society which has its own capability, initiative and inner
strength," Wahid stressed.
</P>
<P>
"It is saddening to learn the fact that after more than 50
years of independence, we are still unsuccessful in managing the
relations among and between various groups, ethnicities, races and
religious followers," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"It is deplorable that blood still sheds, vengeance and hatred
loom large in the hearts of some of our supposedly independence
guardians," Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
The task ahead is, therefore, to rebuild the inter-group
relations in a more creative and humane manner, noted the
president.
</P>
<P>
"We need to formulate a national agenda to be used as a forum
for reconciliations, dialogues, and communications in an attempt
to restore the relations among and between the components of the
society in various regions. We also need to encourage the
emergence of a cultural response against the breakdown of
political communication in our society in several areas," Wahid
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
