<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Venezuelan President Ends Tour of OPEC Nations By Wang Quanfu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
on Tuesday wound up a whirlwind tour of 10 nations of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) within nine
days.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the tour was to invite leaders of the OPEC
countries to attend the second OPEC summit, scheduled for
September 27 and 28 this year in Caracas, the Venezuelan capital.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said Chavez has received confirmation from
six leaders to attend the summit, which is aimed at strengthening
the bloc's unity, its consultation mechanism, and enhancing
Venezuela's leadership in the organization.
</P>
<P>
Chavez was quoted by the press as saying that the heads of
state of Iran, Indonesia, Nigeria, Algeria, Kuwait and Qatar have
confirmed their participation in the summit, and those who would
not be able to attend have promised to send high-level delegations.
</P>
<P>
The achievements of the journey had exceeded the initial
expectations, guaranteeing a success of the summit, the president
said in Algiers, Algeria, the last leg of his tour.
</P>
<P>
Chavez discussed with OPEC leaders a possible alliance between
OPEC state firms and the creation of an OPEC bank.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic step of Chavez's 10-nation trip was his visit
to Iraq, the first by a foreign head of state since the 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
He was warmly welcomed in Baghdad and was impressed as he was
driven through the capital reportedly by Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein himself.
</P>
<P>
He made an impassioned plea to the United Nations for lifting
the decade-long economic sanctions against Iraq, saying: "We have
called many times for the sanctions to be lifted ... because what
is happening in Iraq is unjust and we are happy that we are not
the only ones who feel this way."
</P>
<P>
The visit roused criticism from the United States, which said
the visit could compromise international efforts to contain Saddam
Hussein and force him to comply with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
Shrugging U.S. criticisms, Chavez said: "I'll go to hell if I
want."
</P>
<P>
But Chavez was not alone. He was backed by Indonesian President
Abdurrahman Wahid, who announced that he would visit Baghdad in
the coming weeks for a meeting with Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Despite the friction over the president's visit to Iraq,
Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel said on Tuesday
that the country's relationship with the United States remains
stable, describing the friction as normal "differences" between
allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
