<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Chemical Giant Auctions Bonds Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Dow Chemical, the second
largest chemical producer in the United States, auctioned five-
year bonds worth 300 million U.S. dollars over the Internet on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dow is the first industrial corporation to use an online "Dutch
auction" that allows investors to bid in real time for both the
amount and price of bonds. The company said the bond offering was
successfully placed during a two-hour auction.
</P>
<P>
Dow executives said the use of an Internet-based bond auction
allows the company to raise funds on a more efficient, less costly
basis, and provides the company with access to a broader investor
range as well.
</P>
<P>
In the auction, Dow said, 55 investors were awarded amounts of
up to 40 million dollars, compared to the typical 15 to 20
investors allocated securities in bond offerings of this size.
</P>
<P>
Several companies, including automakers DaimlerChrysler and
Ford Motor, and investment bank Bear Stearns, have reportedly
tried this new way to sell bonds online this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
