<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Association Set to Standardize, Expand Online Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. e-market solutions
provider Commerce One and another 23 companies from 15 countries
have formed an association tasked to standardize and expand
international business-to-business (B2B) e-commerce activity.
</P>
<P>
Commerce One said Tuesday that the newly-born Global Trading
Web Association aims to promote international trade of goods and
services through the use of the Internet. The open, voluntary
venture will also work to remove barriers to trade and provide
alternatives beyond traditional methods of doing business.
</P>
<P>
The association will be a place for international partners to
meet and negotiate transactions, build business relationships,
identify best practices and promote interoperability. Partners can
also issue guidelines, create global directories and develop
services that allow transactions to flow more efficiently for the
good of both member companies and their customers.
</P>
<P>
The new group is an outgrowth of the Global Trading Web, a B2B
online trading community created last year by Commerce One to
provide the advantage of economics of scale for buyers, suppliers
and service providers through independent industry portals. At
present, the association membership consists entirely of core
users of the Global Trading Web. Commerce One, however, said any
company that uses the Global Trading Web even for the smallest
transactions can join in.
</P>
<P>
Among the initial members are global accounting firm Price
Waterhouse Coopers and online marketplaces from Mexico, India,
Australia, Japan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that one of the complexities involving
international B2B e-commerce is settlement procedures between
different banks in different countries. So it's crucial for the
association to include a larger roster of international financial
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
