<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Launch Power Project for Remote Rural Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state-owned newspaper said that the Ministry of Irrigation
and Power is to implement this project by using funds obtained
from the governments of Sweden and Kuwait. The amount of the money
from the two countries is 1,600 million rupees (around 20.3
million dollars) and 771 million rupees (around 9.8 million
dollars), respectively.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Sri Lanka completed the third rural electrification
project which supplied 140,000 rural houses with electricity under
a 3500 million rupee loan from the Asian Development Bank (ADB),
while in 1995, the second rural electrification project, also
funded by the ADB, was completed to supply power for 100,000 rural
houses.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that these projects have increased the
proportion of electrified houses from 43 percent in 1994 to 56.6
percent at the end of 1999, and it expects new projects to help
increase the figure to 80 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Despite expanding electricity services to both rural and
industrial areas, Sri Lanka is faced with a dire power problem.
The country is heavily dependent on hydro power for its
electricity supply but with weather patterns changing and rain
falling short in catchment areas electricity supply has had to be
restricted.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the situation was so bad that power cuts of up to 12
hours a day had to be imposed. Most industrial and commercial
establishments were compelled to purchase their own generators to
keep their establishments functioning.
</P>
<P>
Since then the government has encouraged the generation of
thermal power but still the crisis looms with each delay in
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
This year the Electricity Board has cautioned that, unless more
rain falls in the catchment areas, power cuts may have to be
imposed again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Choose Outstanding Taxi Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Five taxi bodies in Macao on
Wednesday launched a campaign to assess the behavior of taxi
drivers with the help of residents and tourists.
</P>
<P>
Taxi is a major means of public transport in Macao with some 1,
000 taxi drivers. The service of taxi will have a direct impact on
local tourism to great extent, organizers of the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
While taking taxi, residents and tourists can obtain voting
sheets in Chinese, Portuguese and English, and then drop the
sheets into collection boxes at port areas and tourist sites.
</P>
<P>
Taxi passengers can appraise the taxi drivers in the aspects of
the latter's manners, driving security, road familiarity and car
tidiness.
</P>
<P>
The voting sheets are valid till the end of September, and the
final result of appraisal will be announced in October.
Outstanding taxi drivers will be given certificates of merit and
other awards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
