<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gary Hall Misses World Record in 50m Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Gary Hall secured his second
Olympic ticket with an American record but missed the world mark
in the men's 50m freestyle at the U.S. Olympic swimming trials in
Indianapolis Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Hall, 25, who finished second in the 100m freestyle on Sunday,
clocked 21.76 seconds for a national mark, only 0.12 seconds off
the fresh world record of 21.64 set up by Olympic chief rival
Alexander Popov on June 16, 2000 in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Ervin, 19, who won his first trip to Sydney by
finishing fifth for the 100m freestyle relay, claimed his first
outing for an individual event in the Olympic Games by securing
the second place in the 50m freestyle in 21.80.
</P>
<P>
Neil Walker, 24, who was beaten twice in the Olympic Games by
Popov in both the 50m and 100m freestyles, was eliminated from the
50m finals as he only
finished in a disappointing third place in 22.12.
</P>
<P>
However, Walker has already secured two outings in the Olympic
Games by
finishing first in the 100m freestyle and second in the 100m
backstroke earlier.
</P>
<P>
Ian Crocker, 17, also claimed his first spot on the U.S.
Olympic swimming team by winning the 100m butterfly in 52.78,
followed by Tommy Hannan in 52.81.
</P>
<P>
Crocker was the latest evidence of a youth movement in the men'
s program as he became the eighth teenager to make the Olympic
team, while only one male teenager of Tom Malchow went to Atlanta
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Amanda Atkins came from behind to win the women's 200m
backstroke in 2:12.97, followed by Lindsay Benko in 2:13.19.
However, their winning timings are far away from the national mark
of 2:08.60 set by Betsy Mitchel, not to mention Hungarian
Krisztina Egerszegi's world mark of 2:06.62.
</P>
<P>
Brooke Bennett also secured her second Olympic spot by
finishing first in the women's 800m freestyle in 8:23.92, after
claiming the second place in the 400m freestyle last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kaitlin Sandeno finished second in 8:28.61, becoming the first
U.S. swimmer to book three berths in the Olympics as she was
triumphed in the 400m medley and became runner-up in the 200m
butterfly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0229 </DOCNO>
