- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French and British aviation administration officials
will meet in Paris Thursday to consider prolonging the flight
suspension of their Concorde supersonic aircraft, said French
Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gayssot said in a communique that the decision by the British
Airways to suspend the flight of Concordes on Tuesday "probably
followed the recommendation of the Bureau of Accident
Investigation (BEA)" of France and its British counterpart, the
AAIB. (France-Britain-Concorde)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France has asked Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi to
mediate the negotiations between the Philippine government and
Muslim rebels on the release of a dozen hostages taken by the
rebels last April, reported the local popular weekly Canard
Enchaine in its latest issue dated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Three French hostages are among the group of tourists who were
captured by Philippine Muslim rebels of Abu Sayyaf in April in a
Malaysian island and then are kept in captivity in the southern
Philippine island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
Canard Enchaine quoted sources as saying that France has asked
Libya to pay for the ransom to the hostage takers and will in
exchange help Libya break its diplomatic isolation. (France-Libya-
Philippines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
announced Tuesday that the world body will resume aid flights to
the Sudan, lifting a week-long suspension that followed a spate of
government bomb attacks on relief aircraft and compounds.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was contained in a statement issued by Annan's
spokesman. The Sudanese government has given the United Nations
assurances that it will be safe to fly. (UN-Sudan-Air Flights)
</P>
