<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Million People in E. Africa Face Severe Food Shortage: FAO Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- About 20 million people in
Eastern Africa are facing severe food shortage and is in urgent
need of food aid, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
warns in its latest report.
</P>
<P>
More than 800,000 people in Tanzania alone need food assistance
as some areas of the country face acute food shortage, the August
issue of FAO's "Food Supply Situation and Crop Prospects in Sub-
Saharan Africa" says.
</P>
<P>
In the Eastern African region, the number of people facing "
critical" food deficits has increased by a staggering 3 million
compared with April this year, according to the FAO report.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, FAO estimates that nearly 3.3 million people need
urgent food aid. Some starvation-related deaths have been reported
among children in the hardest hit areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said that livestock farmers are of particular
concern because they are facing the failure of the fourth
consecutive rainy season in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and Kenya are among 14 sub-Saharan African countries
facing "exceptional food emergencies".
</P>
<P>
Other countries in the same situation include Angola, Burundi,
the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Sierra
Leone, Somalia and Sudan, which are suffering from the impact of
civil wars or conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
