<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Tutu Returns Home From US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
Anglican archbishop Desmond Tutu Thursday returned home from the
United States, where he had lived and worked for the past two
years as a visiting professor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media conference at Cape Town International
Airport upon arrival, Tutu, a Nobel Peace Prize winner, said he
was seeking a much reduced involvement in public affairs.
</P>
<P>
"So those of you who are thinking: the Arch is back, now we are
going to have interviews with him -- this is your last interview,"
he joked.
</P>
<P>
"I really do want to have a much, much reduced public
involvement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the work of the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC) of which he is the chairman, Tutu said the
country had an obligation to those the TRC had identified as
victims of human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
"When I spoke to President (Thabo) Mbeki in September last year,
and more recently when I met in Atlanta with him, there was no
question in his own mind that government would honor its
obligations to the victims," he said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
He also called for vigorous debate on the problems facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
"We must celebrate our differences. We ought to debate
vigorously... because dissent is not necessarily disloyalty," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
