<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Reaffirms Decision to Quit COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has reaffirmed
its willingness to quit the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) next month despite calls by its private sector to
retain membership, newspapers here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Industries and Commerce Minister Idd Simba reiterated in a
report on measures to withdraw from COMESA that the country's
intention is based on its multiple membership in various
international organizations, some of which have similar goals.
</P>
<P>
"The country has opted to remain a member in the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and the East African
Community (EAC) blocs whose aims are similar to COMESA's," Simba
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that by pulling out Tanzania will only lose
Egypt, Eritrea, Djibouti, Ethiopia and the Sudan, which however,
have insignificant trade links with the country.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Chamber of Commerce, Industries and Agriculture
President Elvis Musiba has argued the withdrawal is bound to
affect Tanzania's industrial and agricultural sectors which for
decades had strong ties with those in COMESA member states with a
combined 300 million people.
</P>
<P>
In April, Tanzania rejected a pleading by neighboring Kenya and
Uganda, claiming that it could not remain in all the three
regional blocs because it would have to adopt three individual
stands when negotiating with other regional organization and the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, a founder members of COMESA, announced the pullout
decision in July last year, blaming that a COMESA plan to reduce
customs tariffs for member countries by 90 percent would damage
its budget revenues and undermine local industries.
</P>
<P>
COMESA leaders are worried that other members, who also have
dual membership with SADC, may follow suit due to the problem of
duplication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
