<HEADLINE> Burundi Rebels Threaten to Resume Fight if Peace Deal not Implemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A Burundian Hutu rebel
group, Front for National Liberation (FROLINA), has threatened to
resume fighting if the peace agreement scheduled to be signed on
August 28 will not be smoothly implemented, the independent
Guardian newspaper reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Chairman of the FROLINA National Joseph
Karumba as saying on Wednesday that FROLINA might be forced to go
back home and take up firearms, if the peace talks with moral and
material supports from both the Great Lakes region and
international community would end up as an abortive deal.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group leader said the implementation of a peace deal
should be accompanied by close monitor to avoid further bloodshed
in the tiny central African country in which over 250,000 people
have been slaughtered since a coup in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Some Burundian parties among the 19 involved in the peace
process being carried out in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha
were there "merely to waste time" and were not seriously committed
to the peace process nor manifested political will or seriousness
during the talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the signed peace accord will not be smoothly implemented
simply because of rigidity of few parties, FROLINA might opt for
going back to the bush," Karumba warned.
</P>
<P>
He stressed it was the hope of his party to see that the
international community and the Great Lakes region would not allow
any sort of obstruction to the signing of a peace accord later
this month.
</P>
<P>
However, the 19 parties featuring in the Arusha talks have not
solved several key issues, including who is going to lead the
transitional government and the timing of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The international facilitator in Burundi conflict, former South
African President Nelson Mandela is making efforts at different
levels for the parties to break the deadlock on the issues before
the signing of the final power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
He has invited 23 heads of states to witness the signing of a
peace deal on August 28 in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The White House announced on Wednesday that President Bill
Clinton will visit Arusha at the end of this month to show U.S.
support for the Burundi peace process, which has started more than
two years ago to try to end the ethnic civil fighting between the
minority Tutsis, who control the government, and the majority
Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
