<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Slams Legislators Over Selfishness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has criticized a move by lawmakers to award themselves hefty
allowance "in total disregard of the hard economic conditions" in
the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Last month Kenya's 222 Members of Parliament secretly increased
their travelling allowance from 118,000 shillings (1,600 U.S.
dollars) a month to 336,000 shillings (4,480 dollars), which has
provoked a public outcry.
</P>
<P>
The legislators should have "first considered the economic
depression facing the country" before making such a move, Thursday
's Kenya Times quoted Moi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rise took effect on July 1 and only became public early
this month. In the current Kenya's parliamentary structure, the
president has no influence over matters on salaries and welfare of
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Kenyan legislators passed a bill to arm
themselves with guns and equip themselves with drivers while the
parliament paid the cost. The measure eventually aborted due to
strong opposition from the public. 
</P>
