<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Surveyed to Surpass TV as Key Information Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 16 (Xinhua) -- After only five years as a
widespread communications tool, the Internet is viewed as an
important source of information of the vast majority of Americans
who use the online technology, according to a report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Responses to a select group of questions gave the Internet a
rating higher than for either television or radio, said brief
excerpts of the report from the Center for Communication Policy of
the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA). The full
Internet report is scheduled to be released in October.
</P>
<P>
In fact, more than two-thirds of respondents (67 percent) who
use the Internet consider the technology to be an "important" or "
extremely important" source of information, while 53 percent of
those surveyed rank television and 47 percent rank radio at the
same level.
</P>
<P>
Among non-users, however, only 26 percent ranked the Internet
as an important source of information. Topping the list to them
were books, followed by newspapers, television, radio, magazines
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Opinions varied widely among users and non-users about the
reliability and accuracy of information on the Internet, the
report said. While almost 55 percent of the Internet users said "
most" or "all" information in cyberspace is reliable and accurate,
only a third of non-users shared that opinion.
</P>
<P>
UCLA launched a long-term study last year examining the social,
political and economic effects of computer technology and the
Internet. The study was designed to survey computer users as well
as non-users in the United States, Singapore and Italy and then
expand to other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
