<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed With Dow falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Blue chip stocks on Wall Street
fell Wednesday as growing worries about corporate earnings over
the rest of the year triggered a selloff in retailers and banks.
But the technology shares rose.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 58.61 at 11,008.39,
extending its loss of 109.14 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 9.54 at 3,861.20 but the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 4.58 at 1,479.85.
</P>
<P>
Stocks opened higher in the wake of additional signs that the U.
S. economy is slowing and inflation remains under control. The
Commerce department reported that housing construction fell 3.3
percent in July to the lowest level in at least two years, and
meanwhile the Labor Department said consumer prices rose a mild 0.
2 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
The reports gave investors more confidence that the Federal
Reserve Board will leave interest rates unchanged at a monetary
policy meeting on Tuesday, next week. The board has raised rates
for the six times in the past 14 months in a pre-emptive move to
cool off the U.S. economy and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
But investors sold stocks of retailers and banks in the late
session as worries arose from the slowing economy. They feared
that the Federal Reserve's move to slow the economy could cut
consumers' speeding and therefore undermine earnings prospects
particularly for retailers and banks in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
A selloff in retail and bank stocks dragged the Dow index lower.
Home Depot and Wal-Mart Stores fell while J.P. Morgan and
Citigroup were also lower.
</P>
<P>
A handful of technology stocks drove the Nasdaq index higher.
Yahoo!, eBay and Lycos rose.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.76 at 666.25 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 4.70 at 908.08. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 2.81 at 512.74.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,612 up, 1,263 down and 485
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 926.79 million shares from 891.88
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
