<TEXT>
<P>
In a short speech at the Burbank Airport, Gore declared "we're
the new guard and we're going to bring positive change to the
United States of America."
</P>
<P>
The vice-president, who will deliver the most important speech
of his life when he accepts the Democratic presidential nomination
Thursday, was greeted by his running mate Joe Lieberman,
California Gov. Gray Davis, Los Angeles mayor Richard Riordan and
several hundred cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
"The victory starts in California," he told a welcoming rally
at Burbank Airport, running mate Joseph Lieberman at his side. "`I
need your help to fight for you."
</P>
<P>
Gore arrived moments before the Democratic National Convention
was called into session for its third day, to ratify his
nomination and Lieberman's, and to hear the vice-presidential
nominee's acceptance address and the presidential nominee's
address on Wednesday night and Thursday night respectively.
</P>
<P>
Previewing his speech, Gore told his supporters, "there are
some big choices we have to make and I'm looking forward to
addressing the nation at the convention podium tomorrow night with
some specific, hard choices that I believe we have to make in
order to ensure that we have a bright future."
</P>
<P>
"You deserve to know exactly what the candidates are proposing
to do so you can make an informed judgment. I'm going to tell you,
" Gore added.
</P>
<P>
A poll by the Voter.com Internet service found Gore had slipped
two points further behind Republican nominee, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, during the first two days of the four-day convention.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Gore's slippage, if confirmed by other surveys,
might have reflected a voter backlash against the rhetoric at the
convention, including a sharp attack on Bush by civil rights
leader Jesse Jackson and an appearance by Massachusetts Sen.
Edward Kennedy, a liberal icon who is less popular with
independent voters.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also noted that President Clinton was slated to boost
his deputy in his speech on Monday evening but devoted most of his
speech to his own accomplishments over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
Gore said his address accepting the Democratic nomination on
Thursday night will spell out the "specific, hard choices" the
nation faces as voters decide between him and Republican nominee
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
Gore listed some of his proposals: better pay for teachers, an
increase in the minimum wage, legislation to guarantee patients'
rights in HMOs, prescription drug benefits in Medicare, a hate
crimes law, mandatory gun locks, affirmative action, cleaner air
and water.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said the issues Gore will highlight in his own
speech have been clear for days, and he used a campaign appearance
with President Clinton on Tuesday to test-drive some rhetoric,
arguing for tax cuts aimed at workers, health care for the young
and elderly and education for all.  
</P>
