<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Kinshasa to Honor Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Wednesday urged the Congolese government to honor the 1999 Lusaka
agreement and move to bring about an end to the conflict in the
African country.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Kinshasa government will reconsider its
refusal to honor the agreement it has signed and will join with
other parties in working toward the peaceful resolution of the
Congolese conflict," spokesman Philip Reeker said.
</P>
<P>
Reeker expressed regret that a summit meeting of 10 African
presidents which ended in Lusaka, Zambia, on Tuesday failed to
reach agreement on next steps to deal with the conflict in the
Congo.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington continues to believe that the peace
agreement signed in Lusaka in 1999 "represents the most viable
means of achieving a just and stable peace for the peoples of the
Congo and the Great Lakes region."
</P>
<P>
Except for the Congolese government, he said, all parties to
the conflict have affirmed their collective desire to create
conditions for the full implementation of the Lusaka agreement.
</P>
<P>
At the Lusaka summit called by the Southern African Development
Community, Congolese President Laurent Kabila reportedly refused
to give ground on two key issues: the deployment of U.N. troops
and his rejection of former Botswana leader Ketumile Masire as the
organizer of all-party talks on the political future of the former
Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
