<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Intelligence Detects No Sign of Life on Sunken Kursk Submarine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. intelligence said on
Wednesday that it had detected no sign of life on board of the
Russian Submarine Kursk since it sank at the bottom of the Barents
Sea last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence officials said they had seen no evidence of, or
heard no evidence of survivors on the Submarine, on board of which
there are 116 sailors.
</P>
<P>
They said they did not know whether anyone survived the initial
incident or not.
</P>
<P>
The officials believed that the Kursk Submarine went down
because of an explosion on board and not because of a collision.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. intelligence would not say how they collected
information about the Kursk, but said that no radio communications
or banging on the hull had been detected. The officials however
cautioned that did not fully rule out survivors on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
