<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Clears GM-Fiat Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Wednesday that it has approved a cooperation agreement between the
U.S. automaker General Motors and its Italian counterpart Fiat
because their proposed joint activities would meet European Union'
s competition rules and benefit consumers.
</P>
<P>
The two carmakers' agreement focuses on the areas of
powertrains, joint-purchase of car components among other
activities, which the EU executive Commission said would improve
the companies' ability to compete with other car manufacturers in
terms of quality, safety standards and prices.
</P>
<P>
"After an analysis and consultation of interested third parties,
" the EU executive believes that although Fiat and General Motors
will coordinate, on an exclusive basis, certain activities, the
alliance should benefit consumers.
</P>
<P>
The two automakers told the EU in June that they had agreed to
set up joint ventures in Europe and Latin America. The EU filed
the agreement for regulatory clearance since then.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said components and parts account for a
considerable share of the cost of a new car and the increase in
the two companies' bargaining power could result in substantial
savings which would be passed on to the consumer in terms of
better safety standards and lower prices. It means the cooperation
conditions for an exemption from the EU competition rules are met.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation agreement provides for the creation of a
powertrain joint venture to be located in Turin, Italy, and a
purchasing joint venture to be based in Russelsheim in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
