<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The European Union (EU) will extend a loan of 70
million euros (63 million U.S. dollars) to Turkey's eastern least
developed provinces to finance a variety of development projects,
reported Anatolia News Agency on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sahabettin Ozaslaner, the governor of Van province, said
Wednesday that Van, Bitlis and Hakkari provinces had been chosen as
pilot regions for the development projects in the process of
structural adjustment with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU funds will be used in urgent projects like purification
facilities, sewer systems, rehabilitation of streams, water supply,
environmental protection and cleaning of lakes, development of
tourism and construction of village roads.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Abu Dhabi Marine Operating Company (ADMA-OPCO)
is carrying out a number of development projects in a bid to
increase oil discovery in the offshore fields.
</P>
<P>
The company, which operates the exploration, development and
production activities of oil and gas in Abu Dhabi's offshore
concession area, has two major fields, Umm Shaif and Zakum.
</P>
<P>
Among the projects are the Umm Shaif Crustal Injection Project,
which will enhance oil production by installing facilities and
digging wells for auto-injection of 600 mmscfd gas from the Umm
Shaif Khuff reservoir into the Umm Shaif Arab C and Arab D
reservoirs. It is expected to be completed by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Another project is the Zakum Pilot Gas Injection Project, which
includes compression and injection facilities and wells to inject a
total of 200 mmscfd associated gas into Lower and Upper Zakum
fields. The project is expected to be completed by September.
</P>
<P>
Zakum is the second largest offshore oilfield in the Gulf area
and ranks amongst the 10 largest fields in the world.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Jordan and Palestine have reached an agreement on
setting up a joint technical committee for the establishment of a
common industrial zone near Jericho city along the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to set up a panel by the two
countries' private sector to put forward proposals for boosting
bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed on the sidelines of the Jordanian
Industrial Exhibition held in the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- A cooperation contract was recently inked in Dubai
between Mubarak Abdullah al-Swaikat Company and European S.G.S.C.
Company, which is specialized in the production and maintenance
of turbines, jet and helicopter gear boxes and power plants.
</P>
<P>
Both parties agreed that Dubai would be the main center of
cooperation which would cover the Middle East and Africa, reported
Al-Hayat newspaper on Wednesday. The contract provides for
establishing a center for maintaining and repairing turbines at Ali
Mount Port and offering services of renting helicopters and private
planes.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Transport Ibrahim el-Demiri said
on Tuesday that Egypt has planned to upgrade the transportation
sector over 30 years at an estimated cost of 150 billion Egyptian
pounds (43.48 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
El-Demiri told the country's Middle East News Agency that the
Egyptian government welcomes investors at home and abroad to invest
in the construction of roads, airports and seaports.
</P>
<P>
Egypt spent about 190 billion pounds (55 billion dollars) from
1981 to 1997 in the transportation sector, including increasing the
mileage of railway by 150 percent, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The two lines of subway in Cairo carry more than 700 million
people in a year, effectively easing the traffic in the capital, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilots of Crashed Helicopter Saved by U.S. Vessel: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Iranian pilots missing after
their helicopter crashed into the Persian Gulf Tuesday night have
been reportedly netted alive by an American vessel on the spot, an
informed source at Iran's Foreign Ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry has demanded the Swiss embassy in
Tehran, which also represents U.S. interests in Iran, to launch a
probe into the issue and announce the results, the source told the
Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of the international law, the witnesses and the
rescuers have to cooperate on the health condition and return of
the people suffered in an accident," the unnamed source added.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S. have been hostile to each other since their
relations broke up in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day an official had predicted the survival of the
missing pilot and copilot.
</P>
<P>
"We have evidence to prove that the missing pilot and copilot of
Tuesday night's air crash are alive," Norollah Rezaei Niaraki,
managing-director of the Iranian Helicopter Services Organization
said.
</P>
<P>
A third occupant, identified as a 26-year-old Indian national,
was injured after the helicopter crashed near Saga platform in
Iran's South Pars gas field. Three other people, whose
nationalities are not clear, were rescued unharmed. No cause for
the accident has yet been given.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter was chartered by Iran's South Pars Company and
was carrying the personnel of a Japanese contractor to Kish free
trade zone in Iran's Persian Gulf province of Hormozgan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
