<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Asks for Interim Extension of U.N. Mission in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has recommended a one-month extension of the United
Nations Mission in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), known
as MONUC, to allow time to assess the impact of recent development
in the central African country, a U.N. spokesman said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Mission's current mandate is set to expire on August 31
following the February 24 resolution of the Security Council,
under which Annan is expected to present his next report to the 15-
nation body on the status of MONUC by August 24.
</P>
<P>
However, in a letter to the Security Council released here
Wednesday, Annan requested that the Council consider an interim
extension of the Mission through September 30 to allow sufficient
time to assess the impact of the latest event and to formulate
appropriate recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the "adverse climate" in the DRC had so far
prevented the deployment of MONUC in accordance with the Council
resolutions, the U.N. chief called attention to the persistent
large-scale fighting in many parts of the country, formerly known
as Zaire, and the severe restrictions imposed by the DRC
authorities and other parties on MONUC's freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to the "sustained campaign of vilification"
against MONUC and individual members of its staff, which had
created significant risks to their security.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace process, Annan said, was undergoing "an
extremely challenging phase," requiring substantial reevaluation
not only on the part of its signatories, but also of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The role that MONUC is to play under the current
circumstances remained unclear," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan emphasized that the implications of several
major developments -- including the August 14 summit meeting in
Lusaka, capital of Zambia, and Rwanda's statement about the
disengagement of its forces in Kasai, a DRC town -- should be
fully and taken into consideration before he submitted
recommendations to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council held talks on Tuesday and will make a
decision on August 24 to extend the mandate of the U.N. mission.
The Security Council agreed in February to send 500 cease-fire
observers and 5,500 troops to protect them but has put the plans
on hold because Kinshasa has refused to let them to area under the
government control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
