<HEADLINE> Dominican President Promises Economic Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hipolito Mejia assumed Wednesday as the Dominican president for
the 2000-2004 period at a ceremony held at the National Assembly,
attended by delegations from 30 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
"I will do whatever is necessary to achieve the food security
of the population," said the new president.
</P>
<P>
The new president said that the economy will be reactivated,
jobs will be created, health and education coverage will be
expanded, exports will be stimulated and there will be more
tourist development.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to work to control drug smuggling in the
Dominican Republic, which is a major transshipment point for
cocaine bound for the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mejia, 59, an agronomist, won the May 16 presidential elections
as the candidate of the Dominican Revolutionary Party (PRD).
</P>
<P>
Mejia succeeds Leonel Fernandez, the first modern leader of
this former Spanish colony of 8 million people. The pro-investment
policies and privatization of state monopolies helped boost the
economy by 40 percent in recent years but failed to lift most
Dominicans out of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
