<HEADLINE> France Suspends Concorde's Flying Certificate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS,August 16(Xinhua)-- France suspended the flying
certificate of the Concorde supersonic aircraft on Wednesday,
following an identical decision by the British Civil Aviation
Authority on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The General Direction of the Civil Aviation of France made the
announcement hours after the Bureau of Accident Investigation (BEA)
recommended that the government suspend the flying certificate
until adequate security measures are taken on the plane.
</P>
<P>
Air France and British Airways were the only two air companies
in the world which used Concorde on their Europe-North America air
lines.
</P>
<P>
The flying certificate is issued to each individual plane
considered capable of making safe flight by the civil aviation
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Air France has suspended the flight of its remaining five
Concorde planes after one of such plane crashed on July 25 near
Paris.
</P>
<P>
British Airways suspended the flight of its Concorde planes on
Tuesday, nearly three weeks after the July 25 crash in which 113
people were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
