<HEADLINE> U.S. to Reduce Antidrug Aid for Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States will give
Costa Rica only 2 million dollars in assistance to beef up the
joint patrolling program against drug trafficking,  Costa Rican
President Miguel Angel Rodriguez said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said that the assistance, to be given in equipment in
the year 2001, is far less than the 15 million dollars agreed on
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Some aid has been obtained, not what we have a right to,
according to the signed treaties," said Rodriguez, explaining that
"Washington has not made available the resources budgeted for us.
They will give us one part, but the rest is still pending because
it is a commitment between countries."
</P>
<P>
The treaty for the joint patrolling between the United States
and Costa Rica was signed in October 1999 and became operational
on January 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the treaty, U.S. Navy ships and military personnel
can enter the Costa Rican territory, waters and skies to fight
drug trafficking for a period of 10 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
