<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Calls for End to Hostilities in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday called on all parties to end hostilities in Burundi "
without delay," and to "engage seriously in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The call came in a press statement after the 15-nation Council
held closed-door consultations, which included the updated
briefing by the U.N. Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The statement, read to the press by Security Council President
Agam Hasmy of Malaysia, said, "Members of the Council reiterated
their call on all parties to end hostilities without delay."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council called on all parties to engage
seriously in the peace process and reiterated their strong support
for the facilitation efforts of (former South African) President (
Nelson) Mandela," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council looked forward to working very closely
with the facilitator in determining the appropriate role of the
United Nations," the statement said. "They would reflect further
on the complex issues surrounding the support that the United
Nations could give to any peace agreement."
</P>
<P>
The statement coincided with the meeting in South Africa
between President Pierre Buyoya of Burundi and Mandela, who is
mediating peace negotiations in the central African country. It
was the second time in two weeks Buyoya, who arrived in
Johannesburg, had come to South Africa to consult Mandela in a bid
to end a seven-year war, which is ethnic-based and pitting the
ruling Tutsi-dominated army against the majority Hutu people.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in seven
years of civil war between the army and the Hutu rebels. Neither
the Burundian government nor rebels have accepted a peace plan put
forward earlier this month by mediator Mandela to end the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
