<DOCNO> XIE20000816.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: France, Britain Suspend Flying Certificate of Concorde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- France and Britain Wednesday
suspended the flying certificate of the Concorde supersonic
aircraft, a rare move taken against a plane considered too risky
to fly.
</P>
<P>
After the British Airways suspended the flight of its seven
Concorde planes on Tuesday, doubt is rising as for whether the
plane, often called "the queen of the sky" because of its high
expenses and superb style of design, can ever fly again.
</P>
<P>
France has suspended the flight of all its remaining five
Concorde planes after one of its such planes crashed on July 25
near Paris, killing 113 people.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) in London and the General
Direction of Civil Aviation under the French Ministry of Transport
made the decision after receiving a recommendation from the French
Accident Investigation Bureau (BEA) and the British Air Accidents
Investigation Branch (AAIB).
</P>
<P>
Both the BEA and AAIB said that adequate security measures must
be taken on the plane before it can be allowed to fly again,
especially the part linked with its tires.
</P>
<P>
The cutting and explosion of a tire is considered to be the
primary cause of the crash on July 25, after a metal strip was
found among the debris on the runway of the plane.
</P>
<P>
A fire broke out in the rear part of the Concorde as soon as
the plane took off from the Roissy international airport. Experts
explained that the explosion of the tire could have damaged one or
two reservoirs and caused a massive leakage of oil.
</P>
<P>
But Sir Malcolm Field, president of CAA, said he cannot believe
the explosion of a tire could have brought about such a
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the flying certificate by the civil aviation
authorities is a rare move and means that the plane suspended is
too risky to fly.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the U.S. aviation authorities suspended the DC-10
plane's flying certificate after an air accident, but the
certificate was given back 37 days later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
